org.schema.name: org.schema
org.schema.description:
Schema.org/3DModel
A 3D model represents some kind of 3D content, which may have [[encoding]]s in one or more [[MediaObject]]s. Many 3D formats are available (e.g. see [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:3D_graphics_file_formats)); specific encoding formats can be represented using the [[encodingFormat]] property applied to the relevant [[MediaObject]]. For the
case of a single file published after Zip compression, the convention of appending '+zip' to the [[encodingFormat]] can be used. Geospatial, AR/VR, artistic/animation, gaming, engineering and scientific content can all be represented using [[3DModel]].

EcAsyncHelper.name: EcAsyncHelper
EcAsyncHelper.description:
Pattern (probably similar to Promise) that provides fine grained control over asynchronous execution.
Will iterate over all items in an array and perform 'each(item,callback)'.
Every 'each' needs to call the callback. This callback can be passed down through several asynchronous calls.
When all callbacks have been called, 'after(array)' is called.

Graph.name: Graph
Graph.description:
A graph consisting of a set of vertices of type V set and a set of edges of type E. Edges of this graph type have exactly two endpoints; whether these endpoints must be distinct depends on the implementation.

This interface permits, but does not enforce, any of the following common variations of graphs:

  • directed and undirected edges
  • vertices and edges with attributes (for example, weighted edges)
  • vertices and edges of different types (for example, bipartite or multimodal graphs)
  • parallel edges (multiple edges which connect a single set of vertices)
  • representations as matrices or as adjacency lists or adjacency maps
Extensions or implementations of this interface may enforce or disallow any or all of these variations.

Definitions (with respect to a given vertex v):

  • incoming edge of v: an edge that can be traversed from a neighbor of v to reach v
  • outgoing edge of v: an edge that can be traversed from v to reach some neighbor of v
  • predecessor of v: a vertex at the other end of an incoming edge of v
  • successor of v: a vertex at the other end of an outgoing edge of v
Graph.author: Tom Buskirk (tom.buskirk@eduworks.com)

Hypergraph.name: Hypergraph
Hypergraph.description:
A hypergraph, consisting of a set of vertices of type V and a set of hyperedges of type E which connect the vertices. This is the base interface for all JUNG graph types.

This interface permits, but does not enforce, any of the following common variations of graphs:

  • hyperedges (edges which connect a set of vertices of any size)
  • edges (these have have exactly two endpoints, which may or may not be distinct)
  • self-loops (edges which connect exactly one vertex)
  • directed and undirected edges
  • vertices and edges with attributes (for example, weighted edges)
  • vertices and edges with different constraints or properties (for example, bipartite or multimodal graphs)
  • parallel edges (multiple edges which connect a single set of vertices)
  • internal representations as matrices or as adjacency lists or adjacency maps
Extensions or implementations of this interface may enforce or disallow any or all of these variations.

Notes:

  • The collections returned by Hypergraph instances should be treated in general as if read-only. While they are not contractually guaranteed (or required) to be immutable, this interface does not define the outcome if they are mutated. Mutations should be done via {add,remove}{Edge,Vertex}, or in the constructor.
Hypergraph.author: Tom Buskirk (tom.buskirk@eduworks.com)

EcRemoteIdentityManager.name: EcRemoteIdentityManager
EcRemoteIdentityManager.description:
Logs into and stores/retrieves credentials from a compatible remote server. Performs anonymization of the user.

Requires initialization with server specific salts. Server specific salts prevent co-occurrence attacks, should credentials on one server be compromised (intercepted in transit).

Transmits hashed username, hashed password, and encrypts credentials using the hashed combination of the username and password. This prevents the system storing the credentials from having any knowledge of the user.

Password recovery is done by, when the password changes, creating a cryptographic pad (or perfect cipher) where one half is stored on the server, and the other half is stored with the user. Should the user lose this pad and forget their password, they are not able to recover or reset their password, and their data should be considered lost.
EcRemoteIdentityManager.author: fritz.ray@eduworks.com

Credential.description:
credentialengine.org/Credential
Qualification, achievement, personal or organizational quality, or aspect of an identity typically used to indicate suitability.
The ceterms:Credential class is broadly defined to encompass credentials used across domains and communities of practice. The class should be used only when speaking of credentials in general. Subclasses of ceterms:Credential as defined by Credential Engine (or other communities) should be used when referencing specific types of credentials.
Credential.author: credentialengine.org

CredentialAlignmentObject.name: CredentialAlignmentObject
CredentialAlignmentObject.description:
credentialengine.org/CredentialAlignmentObject
Entity describing an affiliation or association between an entity such as a credential, learning opportunity or assessment and another entity in a structured framework such as a concept scheme, enumerated list, or competency framework.
CredentialAlignmentObject.author: credentialengine.org

CredentialAssertion.name: CredentialAssertion
CredentialAssertion.description:
credentialengine.org/CredentialAssertion
Representation of a credential awarded to a person.
CredentialAssertion.author: credentialengine.org

CredentialComponent.name: CredentialComponent
CredentialComponent.description:
credentialengine.org/CredentialComponent
Resource that identifies another resource that describes qualification, achievement, personal or organizational quality, or aspect of an identity typically used to indicate suitability.
The ceterms:Credential class is broadly defined to encompass credentials used across domains and communities of practice. Subclasses of ceterms:Credential as defined by Credential Engine (or other communities) should be referenced.
CredentialComponent.author: credentialengine.org

CredentialFramework.name: CredentialFramework
CredentialFramework.description:
credentialengine.org/CredentialFramework
Class of all structured sets of conceptual entities intentionally designed for use as value vocabulary terms for description and classification in the credentialing context.
The class includes, but is not limited to, subclasses of specialized concept schemes describing industries, occupations, professions, learning contexts and jobs, as well as specialized subject concept schemes, assessment rubrics, proficiency scales, and competency frameworks.
CredentialFramework.author: credentialengine.org

CredentialOrganization.name: CredentialOrganization
CredentialOrganization.description:
credentialengine.org/CredentialOrganization
Organization that plays one or more key roles in the lifecycle of a credential.
CredentialOrganization.author: credentialengine.org

CredentialPerson.name: CredentialPerson
CredentialPerson.description:
credentialengine.org/CredentialPerson
Person who plays a role as primary agent in a credentialing action.
The ceterms:CredentialPerson class should be used to describe persons directly engaged as primary agent in credentialing actions such as approving, offering, recognizing, renewing and revoking credentials and should not include persons merely affiliated with, or employed by organizations that perform such actions.
CredentialPerson.author: credentialengine.org

CredentialingAction.name: CredentialingAction
CredentialingAction.description:
credentialengine.org/CredentialingAction
Action taken by an agent affecting the status of an object entity.
Since an instance of ceterms:CredentialingAction is a claim that a certain agent has taken the action being described, creation of such a ceterms:CredentialingAction should be reserved to the agent of that action.
CredentialingAction.author: credentialengine.org

Degree.name: Degree
Degree.description:
credentialengine.org/Degree
Academic credential conferred upon completion of a program or course of study, typically over multiple years at a college or university.
Degree.author: credentialengine.org

DigitalBadge.name: DigitalBadge
DigitalBadge.description:
credentialengine.org/DigitalBadge
Badge offered in digital form.
DigitalBadge.author: credentialengine.org

Diploma.name: Diploma
Diploma.description:
credentialengine.org/Diploma
Credential awarded by educational institutions for successful completion of a course of study or its equivalent.
Diploma.author: credentialengine.org

DoctoralDegree.name: DoctoralDegree
DoctoralDegree.description:
credentialengine.org/DoctoralDegree
Highest credential award for students who have completed both a bachelor's degree and a master's degree or their equivalent as well as independent research and/or a significant project or paper.
Equivalent to UNESCO ISCED, Level 8.
DoctoralDegree.author: credentialengine.org

DurationProfile.name: DurationProfile
DurationProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/DurationProfile
Entity describing the temporal aspects of a resource.
Temporal aspects include exact, minimum, and maximum timeframes of an activity.
DurationProfile.author: credentialengine.org

EarningsProfile.name: EarningsProfile
EarningsProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/EarningsProfile
Entity that describes earning and related statistical information for a given credential.
EarningsProfile.author: credentialengine.org

EmploymentOutcomeProfile.name: EmploymentOutcomeProfile
EmploymentOutcomeProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/EmploymentOutcomeProfile
Entity that describes employment outcomes and related statistical information for a given credential.
EmploymentOutcomeProfile.author: credentialengine.org

ExtracurricularComponent.name: ExtracurricularComponent
ExtracurricularComponent.description:
credentialengine.org/ExtracurricularComponent
Resource that identifies an activity, program, or informal learning experience that may be offered or provided by a school, college, or other organization that is not connected to a curriculum.
ExtracurricularComponent.author: credentialengine.org

FinancialAssistanceProfile.name: FinancialAssistanceProfile
FinancialAssistanceProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/FinancialAssistanceProfile
Entity that describes financial assistance that is offered or available.
FinancialAssistanceProfile.author: credentialengine.org

GeneralEducationDevelopment.name: GeneralEducationDevelopment
GeneralEducationDevelopment.description:
credentialengine.org/GeneralEducationDevelopment
Credential awarded by examination that demonstrates that an individual has acquired secondary school-level academic skills.
Equivalent to a secondary school diploma, based on passing a state- or province-selected examination such as GED, HiSET, or TASC; or to an award at UNESCO ISCED 2011 Levels 2 or 3.
GeneralEducationDevelopment.author: credentialengine.org

GeoCoordinates.name: GeoCoordinates
GeoCoordinates.description:
Schema.org/GeoCoordinates
The geographic coordinates of a place or event.
GeoCoordinates.author: schema.org

HoldersProfile.name: HoldersProfile
HoldersProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/HoldersProfile
Entity describing the count and related statistical information of holders of a given credential.
HoldersProfile.author: credentialengine.org

IdentifierValue.name: IdentifierValue
IdentifierValue.description:
credentialengine.org/IdentifierValue
Means of identifying a resource, typically consisting of an alphanumeric token and a context or scheme from which that token originates.
IdentifierValue.author: credentialengine.org

IndustryClassification.name: IndustryClassification
IndustryClassification.description:
credentialengine.org/IndustryClassification
Class of of concept schemes defining industries such as NAICS in the U.S. and ESCO in the European Union.
IndustryClassification.author: credentialengine.org

InstructionalProgramClassification.name: InstructionalProgramClassification
InstructionalProgramClassification.description:
credentialengine.org/InstructionalProgramClassification
Class of concept schemes defining instructional program types such as the CIP codes in the U.S.
InstructionalProgramClassification.author: credentialengine.org

Job.name: Job
Job.description:
credentialengine.org/Job
Set of responsibilities based on work roles within an occupation as defined by an employer.
Job describes an abstraction or template that specific job postings or openings could be instances of.
Job.author: credentialengine.org

JobComponent.name: JobComponent
JobComponent.description:
credentialengine.org/JobComponent
Resource that identifies a work position, employment, or occupation.
JobComponent.author: credentialengine.org

JourneymanCertificate.name: JourneymanCertificate
JourneymanCertificate.description:
credentialengine.org/JourneymanCertificate
Credential awarded to skilled workers on successful completion of an apprenticeship in industry trades and professions.
JourneymanCertificate.author: credentialengine.org

JurisdictionProfile.name: JurisdictionProfile
JurisdictionProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/JurisdictionProfile
Geo-political information about applicable geographic areas and their exceptions.
JurisdictionProfile.author: credentialengine.org

LearningOpportunity.name: LearningOpportunity
LearningOpportunity.description:
credentialengine.org/LearningOpportunity
Structured and unstructured learning and development opportunities based in direct experience, formal and informal study, observation, and involvement in discourse and practice.
Examples of learning opportunities include education and training programs and classes, courses of study, apprenticeship or work experience programs, or other structured experiences intended to serve as educational or training events.
LearningOpportunity.author: credentialengine.org

LearningOpportunityProfile.name: LearningOpportunityProfile
LearningOpportunityProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/LearningOpportunityProfile
Entity describing an educational or training opportunity.
Opportunities include formal and informal educational training programs and classes, apprenticeship or work experience programs, or other structured or unstructured experiences that serve as educational or training activities.
LearningOpportunityProfile.author: credentialengine.org

LearningResource.name: LearningResource
LearningResource.description:
Schema.org/LearningResource
The LearningResource type can be used to indicate [[CreativeWork]]s (whether physical or digital) that have a particular and explicit orientation towards learning, education, skill acquisition, and other educational purposes.

[[LearningResource]] is expected to be used as an addition to a primary type such as [[Book]], [[VideoObject]], [[Product]] etc.

[[EducationEvent]] serves a similar purpose for event-like things (e.g. a [[Trip]]). A [[LearningResource]] may be created as a result of an [[EducationEvent]], for example by recording one.
LearningResource.author: schema.org

License.name: License
License.description:
credentialengine.org/License
Credential awarded by a government agency that constitutes legal authority to do a specific job and/or utilize a specific item, system or infrastructure and are typically earned through some combination of degree or certificate attainment, certifications, assessments, work experience, and/or fees, and are time-limited and must be renewed periodically.
License.author: credentialengine.org

MasterCertificate.name: MasterCertificate
MasterCertificate.description:
credentialengine.org/MasterCertificate
Credential awarded upon demonstration through apprenticeship of the highest level of skills and performance in industry trades and professions.
MasterCertificate.author: credentialengine.org

MasterDegree.name: MasterDegree
MasterDegree.description:
credentialengine.org/MasterDegree
Credential awarded for a graduate level course of study where course work and activities advance skills beyond those of the bachelor's degree or its equivalent.
Equivalent to an award at UNESCO ISCED 2011, Level 7.
MasterDegree.author: credentialengine.org

MicroCredential.name: MicroCredential
MicroCredential.description:
credentialengine.org/MicroCredential
Credential that addresses a subset of field-specific knowledge, skills, or competencies; often developmental with relationships to other micro-credentials and field credentials.
MicroCredential.author: credentialengine.org

Occupation.name: Occupation
Occupation.description:
Schema.org/Occupation
A profession, may involve prolonged training and/or a formal qualification.
Occupation.author: schema.org

OccupationClassification.name: OccupationClassification
OccupationClassification.description:
credentialengine.org/OccupationClassification
Class of concept schemes identifying occupations such as the Standard Occupational Classification (SOC) system in the U.S. and the European Skills/Competences, Qualifications and Occupations (ESCO).
OccupationClassification.author: credentialengine.org

OfferAction.name: OfferAction
OfferAction.description:
credentialengine.org/OfferAction
Action by an authoritative agent offering access to a entity such as a credential, learning opportunity or assessment.
Since an instance of ceterms:CredentialingAction is a claim that a certain agent has taken the action being described, creation of such a ceterms:CredentialingAction should be reserved to the agent of that action.
OfferAction.author: credentialengine.org

OpenBadge.name: OpenBadge
OpenBadge.description:
credentialengine.org/OpenBadge
Visual symbol containing verifiable claims in accordance with the Open Badges specification and delivered digitally.
OpenBadge.author: credentialengine.org

Pathway.name: Pathway
Pathway.description:
credentialengine.org/Pathway
Resource composed of a structured set of PathwayComponents defining points along a route to fulfillment of a goal or objective.
Pathway.author: credentialengine.org

PathwayComponent.name: PathwayComponent
PathwayComponent.description:
credentialengine.org/PathwayComponent
Resource that serves as a defined point along the route of a Pathway which describes an objective and its completion requirements through reference to one or more instances of ComponentCondition.
An instance of PathwayComponent may serve as the goal or destination node of a Pathway.
PathwayComponent.author: credentialengine.org

PathwaySet.name: PathwaySet
PathwaySet.description:
credentialengine.org/PathwaySet
A roadmap of multiple related pathways that lead to one or more destinations.
PathwaySet.author: credentialengine.org

Place.name: Place
Place.description:
Schema.org/Place
Entities that have a somewhat fixed, physical extension.
Place.author: schema.org

ProcessProfile.name: ProcessProfile
ProcessProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/ProcessProfile
Entity describing the type, nature, and other relevant information about a process related to a credential.
ProcessProfile.author: credentialengine.org

ProfessionalDoctorate.name: ProfessionalDoctorate
ProfessionalDoctorate.description:
credentialengine.org/ProfessionalDoctorate
Doctoral degree conferred upon completion of a program providing the knowledge and skills for the recognition, credential, or license required for professional practice.
Equivalent to an award at UNESCO ISCED 2011, Level 8.
ProfessionalDoctorate.author: credentialengine.org

ProficiencyScale.name: ProficiencyScale
ProficiencyScale.description:
credentialengine.org/ProficiencyScale
The class of structured profiles describing discrete levels of expertise and performance mastery.
Proficiency scales define levels of performance (what a person does) as distinct from knowledge of specific information (what a person knows) and outline tasks a person can manage and the skills necessary to progressively accomplish explicit competencies at increasing levels of complexity. Proficiency scales: (1) assist in making judgments about the kinds of tasks related to a competency that a person is able to perform; and (2) to compare the abilities of different persons with regard to achievement of those competencies at different levels.
ProficiencyScale.author: credentialengine.org

ProgressionLevel.name: ProgressionLevel
ProgressionLevel.description:
asn:ProgressionLevel
Identifiable point along a developmental progression of competence, achievement or temporal position.
ProgressionLevel.author: credentialengine.org

ProgressionModel.name: ProgressionModel
ProgressionModel.description:
asn:ProgressionModel
Model of identifiable points along a developmental progression including increasing levels of competence, achievement or temporal position (e.g., "Second Quarter").
ProgressionModel.author: credentialengine.org

QACredentialOrganization.name: QACredentialOrganization
QACredentialOrganization.description:
credentialengine.org/QACredentialOrganization
Quality assurance organization that plays one or more key roles in the lifecycle of a credential, learning program, or assessment.
QACredentialOrganization.author: credentialengine.org

QualityAssuranceCredential.name: QualityAssuranceCredential
QualityAssuranceCredential.description:
credentialengine.org/QualityAssuranceCredential
Credential assuring that an organization, program, or awarded credential meets prescribed requirements and may include development and administration of qualifying examinations.
QualityAssuranceCredential.author: credentialengine.org

QuantitativeValue.name: QuantitativeValue
QuantitativeValue.description:
Schema.org/QuantitativeValue
 A point value or interval for product characteristics and other purposes.
QuantitativeValue.author: schema.org

RecognizeAction.name: RecognizeAction
RecognizeAction.description:
credentialengine.org/RecognizeAction
Action by an independent, neutral, and authoritative agent acknowledging the validity of a resource.
Since an instance of ceterms:CredentialingAction is a claim that a certain agent has taken the action being described, creation of such a ceterms:CredentialingAction should be reserved to the agent of that action.
RecognizeAction.author: credentialengine.org

RegulateAction.name: RegulateAction
RegulateAction.description:
credentialengine.org/RegulateAction
Action by an independent, neutral, and authoritative agent enforcing the legal requirements of a resource.
Since an instance of ceterms:CredentialingAction is a claim that a certain agent has taken the action being described, creation of such a ceterms:CredentialingAction should be reserved to the agent of that action.
RegulateAction.author: credentialengine.org

RenewAction.name: RenewAction
RenewAction.description:
credentialengine.org/RenewAction
Action by an agent renewing an existing credential assertion.
Since an instance of ceterms:CredentialingAction is a claim that a certain agent has taken the action being described, creation of such a ceterms:CredentialingAction should be reserved to the agent of that action.
RenewAction.author: credentialengine.org

ResearchDoctorate.name: ResearchDoctorate
ResearchDoctorate.description:
credentialengine.org/ResearchDoctorate
Doctoral degree conferred for advanced work beyond the master level, including the preparation and defense of a thesis or dissertation based on original research, or the planning and execution of an original project demonstrating substantial artistic or scholarly achievement.
Equivalent to an award at UNESCO ISCED 2011, Level 8.
ResearchDoctorate.author: credentialengine.org

RevocationProfile.name: RevocationProfile
RevocationProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/RevocationProfile
Entity describing conditions and methods by which a credential can be removed from a holder.
RevocationProfile.author: credentialengine.org

RevokeAction.name: RevokeAction
RevokeAction.description:
credentialengine.org/RevokeAction
Action by an agent removing an awarded credential (credential assertion) from the credential holder based on violations or failure of the holder to renew.
Since an instance of ceterms:CredentialingAction is a claim that a certain agent has taken the action being described, creation of such a ceterms:CredentialingAction should be reserved to the agent of that action.
RevokeAction.author: credentialengine.org

RightsAction.name: RightsAction
RightsAction.description:
credentialengine.org/RightsAction
Action asserting legal rights by an agent to possess, defend, transfer, license, and grant conditional access to a credential, learning opportunity, or assessment.
Since an instance of ceterms:CredentialingAction is a claim that a certain agent has taken the action being described, creation of such a ceterms:CredentialingAction should be reserved to the agent of that action.
RightsAction.author: credentialengine.org

RuleSet.name: RuleSet
RuleSet.description:
credentialengine.org/RuleSet
Resource that identifies the rules or methods by which one or more PathwayComponent instances satisfy the requirements of a ComponentCondition.
In the future, there will likely be multiple formally recognized RuleSets.
RuleSet.author: credentialengine.org

RuleSetProfile.name: RuleSetProfile
RuleSetProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/RuleSetProfile
Resource defining the application of a RuleSet to a particular ComponentCondition.
RuleSetProfile.author: credentialengine.org

SecondarySchoolDiploma.name: SecondarySchoolDiploma
SecondarySchoolDiploma.description:
credentialengine.org/SecondarySchoolDiploma
Diploma awarded by secondary education institutions for successful completion of a secondary school program of study.
Equivalent to an award at UNESCO ISCED 2011 Levels 2 or 3.
SecondarySchoolDiploma.author: credentialengine.org

SelectionComponent.name: SelectionComponent
SelectionComponent.description:
credentialengine.org/SelectionComponent
Component which provides a condition which references an array of other components from which components must be selected.
SelectionComponent.author: credentialengine.org

TransferValueProfile.name: TransferValueProfile
TransferValueProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/TransferValueProfile
Description of transfer value of a resource.
TransferValueProfile.author: credentialengine.org

ValueProfile.name: ValueProfile
ValueProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/ValueProfile
A description of value awarded for, required by, or otherwise related to the resource.
ValueProfile.author: credentialengine.org

VerificationServiceProfile.name: VerificationServiceProfile
VerificationServiceProfile.description:
credentialengine.org/VerificationServiceProfile
Entity describing the means by which someone can verify whether a credential has been attained.
Includes, but is not limited to, verification of whether quality assurance credentials have been issued for organizations, learning opportunities, and assessments.
VerificationServiceProfile.author: credentialengine.org

WorkExperienceComponent.name: WorkExperienceComponent
WorkExperienceComponent.description:
credentialengine.org/WorkExperienceComponent
Resource describing an activity or training through which a person gains job experience.
WorkExperienceComponent.author: credentialengine.org

WorkRole.name: WorkRole
WorkRole.description:
credentialengine.org/WorkRole
Collection of tasks and competencies that embody a particular function in one or more jobs.
WorkRole.author: credentialengine.org

EcLinkedData\n/ module.exports = class E.description:
Represents a JSON-LD linked data object and performs serialization.
Note: Serialization and deserialization remove parameters that begin with '@'.
Note: This Linked Data Object is not assumed to have an @id field.
EcLinkedData\n/ module.exports = class E.author: fritz.ray@eduworks.com

3DModel.name: 3DModel
3DModel.description:
Schema.org/3DModel
A 3D model represents some kind of 3D content, which may have [[encoding]]s in one or more [[MediaObject]]s. Many 3D formats are available (e.g. see [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:3D_graphics_file_formats)); specific encoding formats can be represented using the [[encodingFormat]] property applied to the relevant [[MediaObject]]. For the
case of a single file published after Zip compression, the convention of appending '+zip' to the [[encodingFormat]] can be used. Geospatial, AR/VR, artistic/animation, gaming, engineering and scientific content can all be represented using [[3DModel]].
3DModel.author: schema.org

AMRadioChannel.name: AMRadioChannel
AMRadioChannel.description:
Schema.org/AMRadioChannel
A radio channel that uses AM.
AMRadioChannel.author: schema.org

APIReference.name: APIReference
APIReference.description:
Schema.org/APIReference
Reference documentation for application programming interfaces (APIs).
APIReference.author: schema.org

AboutPage.name: AboutPage
AboutPage.description:
Schema.org/AboutPage
Web page type: About page.
AboutPage.author: schema.org

AcceptAction.name: AcceptAction
AcceptAction.description:
Schema.org/AcceptAction
The act of committing to/adopting an object.

Related actions:

* [[RejectAction]]: The antonym of AcceptAction.
AcceptAction.author: schema.org

Accommodation.name: Accommodation
Accommodation.description:
Schema.org/Accommodation An accommodation is a place that can accommodate human beings, e.g. a hotel room, a camping pitch, or a meeting room. Many accommodations are for overnight stays, but this is not a mandatory requirement. For more specific types of accommodations not defined in schema.org, one can use additionalType with external vocabularies.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
Accommodation.author: schema.org

AccountingService.name: AccountingService
AccountingService.description:
Schema.org/AccountingService
Accountancy business.\n\nAs a [[LocalBusiness]] it can be described as a [[provider]] of one or more [[Service]]\(s).
AccountingService.author: schema.org

AchieveAction.name: AchieveAction
AchieveAction.description:
Schema.org/AchieveAction
The act of accomplishing something via previous efforts. It is an instantaneous action rather than an ongoing process.
AchieveAction.author: schema.org

Action.name: Action
Action.description:
Schema.org/Action
An action performed by a direct agent and indirect participants upon a direct object. Optionally happens at a location with the help of an inanimate instrument. The execution of the action may produce a result. Specific action sub-type documentation specifies the exact expectation of each argument/role.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/04/announcing-schemaorg-actions.html) and [Actions overview document](schema:docs/actions.html).
Action.author: schema.org

ActionAccessSpecification.name: ActionAccessSpecification
ActionAccessSpecification.description:
Schema.org/ActionAccessSpecification
A set of requirements that a must be fulfilled in order to perform an Action.
ActionAccessSpecification.author: schema.org

ActionStatusType.name: ActionStatusType
ActionStatusType.description:
Schema.org/ActionStatusType
The status of an Action.
ActionStatusType.author: schema.org

ActivateAction.name: ActivateAction
ActivateAction.description:
Schema.org/ActivateAction
The act of starting or activating a device or application (e.g. starting a timer or turning on a flashlight).
ActivateAction.author: schema.org

AddAction.name: AddAction
AddAction.description:
Schema.org/AddAction
The act of editing by adding an object to a collection.
AddAction.author: schema.org

AdministrativeArea.name: AdministrativeArea
AdministrativeArea.description:
Schema.org/AdministrativeArea
A geographical region, typically under the jurisdiction of a particular government.
AdministrativeArea.author: schema.org

AdvertiserContentArticle.name: AdvertiserContentArticle
AdvertiserContentArticle.description:
Schema.org/AdvertiserContentArticle
An [[Article]] that an external entity has paid to place or to produce to its specifications. Includes [advertorials](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Advertorial), sponsored content, native advertising and other paid content.
AdvertiserContentArticle.author: schema.org

AggregateOffer.name: AggregateOffer
AggregateOffer.description:
Schema.org/AggregateOffer
When a single product is associated with multiple offers (for example, the same pair of shoes is offered by different merchants), then AggregateOffer can be used.\n\nNote: AggregateOffers are normally expected to associate multiple offers that all share the same defined [[businessFunction]] value, or default to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell if businessFunction is not explicitly defined.
AggregateOffer.author: schema.org

AggregateRating.name: AggregateRating
AggregateRating.description:
Schema.org/AggregateRating
The average rating based on multiple ratings or reviews.
AggregateRating.author: schema.org

AgreeAction.name: AgreeAction
AgreeAction.description:
Schema.org/AgreeAction
The act of expressing a consistency of opinion with the object. An agent agrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.
AgreeAction.author: schema.org

Airline.name: Airline
Airline.description:
Schema.org/Airline
An organization that provides flights for passengers.
Airline.author: schema.org

AlignmentObject.name: AlignmentObject
AlignmentObject.description:
Schema.org/AlignmentObject
An intangible item that describes an alignment between a learning resource and a node in an educational framework.

Should not be used where the nature of the alignment can be described using a simple property, for example to express that a resource [[teaches]] or [[assesses]] a competency.
AlignmentObject.author: schema.org

AllocateAction.name: AllocateAction
AllocateAction.description:
Schema.org/AllocateAction
The act of organizing tasks/objects/events by associating resources to it.
AllocateAction.author: schema.org

AmpStory.name: AmpStory
AmpStory.description:
Schema.org/AmpStory
A creative work with a visual storytelling format intended to be viewed online, particularly on mobile devices.
AmpStory.author: schema.org

AnalysisNewsArticle.name: AnalysisNewsArticle
AnalysisNewsArticle.description:
Schema.org/AnalysisNewsArticle
An AnalysisNewsArticle is a [[NewsArticle]] that, while based on factual reporting, incorporates the expertise of the author/producer, offering interpretations and conclusions.
AnalysisNewsArticle.author: schema.org

AnatomicalStructure.name: AnatomicalStructure
AnatomicalStructure.description:
Schema.org/AnatomicalStructure
Any part of the human body, typically a component of an anatomical system. Organs, tissues, and cells are all anatomical structures.
AnatomicalStructure.author: schema.org

AnatomicalSystem.name: AnatomicalSystem
AnatomicalSystem.description:
Schema.org/AnatomicalSystem
An anatomical system is a group of anatomical structures that work together to perform a certain task. Anatomical systems, such as organ systems, are one organizing principle of anatomy, and can includes circulatory, digestive, endocrine, integumentary, immune, lymphatic, muscular, nervous, reproductive, respiratory, skeletal, urinary, vestibular, and other systems.
AnatomicalSystem.author: schema.org

Answer.name: Answer
Answer.description:
Schema.org/Answer
An answer offered to a question; perhaps correct, perhaps opinionated or wrong.
Answer.author: schema.org

Apartment.name: Apartment
Apartment.description: Schema.org/Apartment An apartment (in American English) or flat (in British English) is a self-contained housing unit (a type of residential real estate) that occupies only part of a building (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apartment).
Apartment.author: schema.org

AppendAction.name: AppendAction
AppendAction.description:
Schema.org/AppendAction
The act of inserting at the end if an ordered collection.
AppendAction.author: schema.org

ApplyAction.name: ApplyAction
ApplyAction.description:
Schema.org/ApplyAction
The act of registering to an organization/service without the guarantee to receive it.

Related actions:

* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, ApplyAction has no guarantees that the application will be accepted.
ApplyAction.author: schema.org

ApprovedIndication.name: ApprovedIndication
ApprovedIndication.description:
Schema.org/ApprovedIndication
An indication for a medical therapy that has been formally specified or approved by a regulatory body that regulates use of the therapy; for example, the US FDA approves indications for most drugs in the US.
ApprovedIndication.author: schema.org

ArriveAction.name: ArriveAction
ArriveAction.description:
Schema.org/ArriveAction
The act of arriving at a place. An agent arrives at a destination from a fromLocation, optionally with participants.
ArriveAction.author: schema.org

Artery.name: Artery
Artery.description:
Schema.org/Artery
A type of blood vessel that specifically carries blood away from the heart.
Artery.author: schema.org

Article.name: Article
Article.description:
Schema.org/Article
An article, such as a news article or piece of investigative report. Newspapers and magazines have articles of many different types and this is intended to cover them all.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).
Article.author: schema.org

AskAction.name: AskAction
AskAction.description:
Schema.org/AskAction
The act of posing a question / favor to someone.

Related actions:

* [[ReplyAction]]: Appears generally as a response to AskAction.
AskAction.author: schema.org

AskPublicNewsArticle.name: AskPublicNewsArticle

AskPublicNewsArticle.author: schema.org

AssessAction.name: AssessAction
AssessAction.description:
Schema.org/AssessAction
The act of forming one's opinion, reaction or sentiment.

AssignAction.name: AssignAction

Atlas.name: Atlas

Attorney.name: Attorney

Audience.name: Audience

BackgroundNewsArticle.name: BackgroundNewsArticle

Schema.org/BackgroundNewsArticle
A [[NewsArticle]] providing historical context, definition and detail on a specific topic (aka "explainer" or "backgrounder"). For example, an in-depth article or frequently-asked-questions ([FAQ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FAQ)) document on topics such as Climate Change or the European Union. Other kinds of background material from a non-news setting are often described using [[Book]] or [[Article]], in particular [[ScholarlyArticle]]. See also [[NewsArticle]] for related vocabulary from a learning/education perspective.
BackgroundNewsArticle.author: schema.org

BankAccount.name: BankAccount
BankAccount.description:
Schema.org/BankAccount
A product or service offered by a bank whereby one may deposit, withdraw or transfer money and in some cases be paid interest.
BankAccount.author: schema.org

Barcode.name: Barcode
Barcode.description:
Schema.org/Barcode
An image of a visual machine-readable code such as a barcode or QR code.
Barcode.author: schema.org

BedAndBreakfast.name: BedAndBreakfast
BedAndBreakfast.description:
Schema.org/BedAndBreakfast Bed and breakfast.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
BedAndBreakfast.author: schema.org

BedDetails.name: BedDetails
BedDetails.description:
Schema.org/BedDetails
An entity holding detailed information about the available bed types, e.g. the quantity of twin beds for a hotel room. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you can use bed directly with a text. See also [[BedType]] (under development).
BedDetails.author: schema.org

BedType.name: BedType
BedType.description:

A type of bed. This is used for indicating the bed or beds available in an accommodation.

BefriendAction.name: BefriendAction
BefriendAction.description:
Schema.org/BefriendAction

BloodTest.name: BloodTest
BloodTest.description:

A medical test performed on a sample of a patient's blood.
BloodTest.author: schema.org

BoardingPolicyType.name: BoardingPolicyType
BoardingPolicyType.description:
Schema.org/BoardingPolicyType
A type of boarding policy used by an airline.
BoardingPolicyType.author: schema.org

BoatReservation.name: BoatReservation
BoatReservation.description:
Schema.org/BoatReservation
A reservation for boat travel.

Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].
BoatReservation.author: schema.org

BoatTerminal.name: BoatTerminal
BoatTerminal.description:
Schema.org/BoatTerminal
A terminal for boats, ships, and other water vessels.

BoatTrip.name: BoatTrip
BoatTrip.description:

BodyMeasurementTypeEnumeration.name: BodyMeasurementTypeEnumeration
BodyMeasurementTypeEnumeration.description:
Schema.org/BodyMeasurementTypeEnumeration
Enumerates types (or dimensions) of a person's body measurements, for example for fitting of clothes.
BodyMeasurementTypeEnumeration.author: schema.org

BodyOfWater.name: BodyOfWater
BodyOfWater.description:
Schema.org/BodyOfWater
A body of water, such as a sea, ocean, or lake.
BodyOfWater.author: schema.org

Bone.name: Bone
Bone.description:
Schema.org/Bone
Rigid connective tissue that comprises up the skeletal structure of the human body.
Bone.author: schema.org

BookFormatType.name: BookFormatType
BookFormatType.description:
Schema.org/BookFormatType
The publication format of the book.
BookFormatType.author: schema.org

BookSeries.name: BookSeries
BookSeries.description:
Schema.org/BookSeries
A series of books. Included books can be indicated with the hasPart property.
BookSeries.author: schema.org

BookmarkAction.name: BookmarkAction
BookmarkAction.description:
Schema.org/BookmarkAction
An agent bookmarks/flags/labels/tags/marks an object.
BookmarkAction.author: schema.org

BorrowAction.name: BorrowAction
BorrowAction.description:
Schema.org/BorrowAction
The act of obtaining an object under an agreement to return it at a later date. Reciprocal of LendAction.

Related actions:

* [[LendAction]]: Reciprocal of BorrowAction.
BorrowAction.author: schema.org

BrainStructure.name: BrainStructure
BrainStructure.description:
Schema.org/BrainStructure
Any anatomical structure which pertains to the soft nervous tissue functioning as the coordinating center of sensation and intellectual and nervous activity.
BrainStructure.author: schema.org

Brand.name: Brand
Brand.description:
Schema.org/Brand
A brand is a name used by an organization or business person for labeling a product, product group, or similar.
Brand.author: schema.org

BreadcrumbList.name: BreadcrumbList
BreadcrumbList.description:
Schema.org/BreadcrumbList
A BreadcrumbList is an ItemList consisting of a chain of linked Web pages, typically described using at least their URL and their name, and typically ending with the current page.\n\nThe [[position]] property is used to reconstruct the order of the items in a BreadcrumbList The convention is that a breadcrumb list has an [[itemListOrder]] of [[ItemListOrderAscending]] (lower values listed first), and that the first items in this list correspond to the "top" or beginning of the breadcrumb trail, e.g. with a site or section homepage. The specific values of 'position' are not assigned meaning for a BreadcrumbList, but they should be integers, e.g. beginning with '1' for the first item in the list.
BreadcrumbList.author: schema.org

BroadcastChannel.name: BroadcastChannel
BroadcastChannel.description:
Schema.org/BroadcastChannel
A unique instance of a BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.
BroadcastChannel.author: schema.org

BroadcastEvent.name: BroadcastEvent
BroadcastEvent.description:
Schema.org/BroadcastEvent
An over the air or online broadcast event.
BroadcastEvent.author: schema.org

BroadcastFrequencySpecification.name: BroadcastFrequencySpecification
BroadcastFrequencySpecification.description:
Schema.org/BroadcastFrequencySpecification
The frequency in MHz and the modulation used for a particular BroadcastService.
BroadcastFrequencySpecification.author: schema.org

BroadcastService.name: BroadcastService
BroadcastService.description:
Schema.org/BroadcastService
A delivery service through which content is provided via broadcast over the air or online.
BroadcastService.author: schema.org

BrokerageAccount.name: BrokerageAccount
BrokerageAccount.description:
Schema.org/BrokerageAccount
An account that allows an investor to deposit funds and place investment orders with a licensed broker or brokerage firm.
BrokerageAccount.author: schema.org

BusOrCoach.name: BusOrCoach
BusOrCoach.description:
Schema.org/BusOrCoach
A bus (also omnibus or autobus) is a road vehicle designed to carry passengers. Coaches are luxury busses, usually in service for long distance travel.
BusOrCoach.author: schema.org

BusReservation.name: BusReservation
BusReservation.description:
Schema.org/BusReservation
A reservation for bus travel. \n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].
BusReservation.author: schema.org

BusTrip.name: BusTrip
BusTrip.description:
Schema.org/BusTrip
A trip on a commercial bus line.
BusTrip.author: schema.org

BusinessAudience.name: BusinessAudience
BusinessAudience.description:
Schema.org/BusinessAudience
A set of characteristics belonging to businesses, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.
BusinessAudience.author: schema.org

BusinessEntityType.name: BusinessEntityType
BusinessEntityType.description:
Schema.org/BusinessEntityType
A business entity type is a conceptual entity representing the legal form, the size, the main line of business, the position in the value chain, or any combination thereof, of an organization or business person.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Business
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Enduser
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PublicInstitution
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Reseller
BusinessEntityType.author: schema.org

BusinessFunction.name: BusinessFunction
BusinessFunction.description:
Schema.org/BusinessFunction
The business function specifies the type of activity or access (i.e., the bundle of rights) offered by the organization or business person through the offer. Typical are sell, rental or lease, maintenance or repair, manufacture / produce, recycle / dispose, engineering / construction, or installation. Proprietary specifications of access rights are also instances of this class.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ConstructionInstallation
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Dispose
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Maintain
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ProvideService
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Repair
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Buy
BusinessFunction.author: schema.org

BuyAction.name: BuyAction
BuyAction.description:
Schema.org/BuyAction
The act of giving money to a seller in exchange for goods or services rendered. An agent buys an object, product, or service from a seller for a price. Reciprocal of SellAction.
BuyAction.author: schema.org

CDCPMDRecord.name: CDCPMDRecord
CDCPMDRecord.description:
Schema.org/CDCPMDRecord
A CDCPMDRecord is a data structure representing a record in a CDC tabular data format
     used for hospital data reporting. See [documentation](/docs/cdc-covid.html) for details, and the linked CDC materials for authoritative
     definitions used as the source here.
CDCPMDRecord.author: schema.org

CableOrSatelliteService.name: CableOrSatelliteService
CableOrSatelliteService.description:
Schema.org/CableOrSatelliteService
A service which provides access to media programming like TV or radio. Access may be via cable or satellite.
CableOrSatelliteService.author: schema.org

CafeOrCoffeeShop.name: CafeOrCoffeeShop
CafeOrCoffeeShop.description:
Schema.org/CafeOrCoffeeShop
A cafe or coffee shop.
CafeOrCoffeeShop.author: schema.org

Campground.name: Campground
Campground.description:
Schema.org/Campground
A camping site, campsite, or [[Campground]] is a place used for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically containing individual [[CampingPitch]] locations. \n\n
In British English a campsite is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground. In American English the term campsite generally means an area where an individual, family, group, or military unit can pitch a tent or park a camper; a campground may contain many campsites (Source: Wikipedia see [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite)).\n\n

See also the dedicated [document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations](/docs/hotels.html).
Campground.author: schema.org

CampingPitch.name: CampingPitch
CampingPitch.description:
Schema.org/CampingPitch
A [[CampingPitch]] is an individual place for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically being part of a larger camping site, or [[Campground]].\n\n
In British English a campsite, or campground, is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground. In American English the term campsite generally means an area where an individual, family, group, or military unit can pitch a tent or park a camper; a campground may contain many campsites.
(Source: Wikipedia see [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite)).\n\n
See also the dedicated [document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations](/docs/hotels.html).
CampingPitch.author: schema.org

Canal.name: Canal
Canal.description:
Schema.org/Canal
A canal, like the Panama Canal.
Canal.author: schema.org

CancelAction.name: CancelAction
CancelAction.description:
Schema.org/CancelAction
The act of asserting that a future event/action is no longer going to happen.

Related actions:

* [[ConfirmAction]]: The antonym of CancelAction.
CancelAction.author: schema.org

Car.name: Car
Car.description:
Schema.org/Car
A car is a wheeled, self-powered motor vehicle used for transportation.
Car.author: schema.org

CarUsageType.name: CarUsageType
CarUsageType.description:
Schema.org/CarUsageType
A value indicating a special usage of a car, e.g. commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi.
CarUsageType.author: schema.org

CategoryCodeSet.name: CategoryCodeSet
CategoryCodeSet.description:
Schema.org/CategoryCodeSet
A set of Category Code values.
CategoryCodeSet.author: schema.org

Chapter.name: Chapter
Chapter.description:

One of the sections into which a book is divided. A chapter usually has a section number or a name.

CheckAction.description:
Schema.org/CheckAction
An agent inspects, determines, investigates, inquires, or examines an object's accuracy, quality, condition, or state.
CheckAction.author: schema.org

CheckInAction.name: CheckInAction
CheckInAction.description:
Schema.org/CheckInAction
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their arrival by registering/confirming for a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check in) or at a place (e.g. hotel), possibly resulting in a result (boarding pass, etc).

Related actions:

* [[CheckOutAction]]: The antonym of CheckInAction.
* [[ArriveAction]]: Unlike ArriveAction, CheckInAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the start of a previously reserved service.
* [[ConfirmAction]]: Unlike ConfirmAction, CheckInAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the *start* of a previously reserved service rather than its validity/existence.
CheckInAction.author: schema.org

CheckOutAction.name: CheckOutAction
CheckOutAction.description:
Schema.org/CheckOutAction
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their departure of a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check in) or place (e.g. hotel).

Related actions:

* [[CheckInAction]]: The antonym of CheckOutAction.
* [[DepartAction]]: Unlike DepartAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.
* [[CancelAction]]: Unlike CancelAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.
CheckOutAction.author: schema.org

CheckoutPage.name: CheckoutPage
CheckoutPage.description:
Schema.org/CheckoutPage
Web page type: Checkout page.
CheckoutPage.author: schema.org

ChooseAction.name: ChooseAction
ChooseAction.description:
Schema.org/ChooseAction
The act of expressing a preference from a set of options or a large or unbounded set of choices/options.
ChooseAction.author: schema.org

CivicStructure.name: CivicStructure
CivicStructure.description:
Schema.org/CivicStructure
A public structure, such as a town hall or concert hall.
CivicStructure.author: schema.org

Claim.name: Claim
Claim.description:
Schema.org/Claim
A [[Claim]] in Schema.org represents a specific, factually-oriented claim that could be the [[itemReviewed]] in a [[ClaimReview]]. The content of a claim can be summarized with the [[text]] property. Variations on well known claims can have their common identity indicated via [[sameAs]] links, and summarized with a [[name]]. Ideally, a [[Claim]] description includes enough contextual information to minimize the risk of ambiguity or inclarity. In practice, many claims are better understood in the context in which they appear or the interpretations provided by claim reviews.

 Beyond [[ClaimReview]], the Claim type can be associated with related creative works - for example a [[ScholarlyArticle]] or [[Question]] might be [[about]] some [[Claim]].

 At this time, Schema.org does not define any types of relationship between claims. This is a natural area for future exploration.
Claim.author: schema.org

ClaimReview.name: ClaimReview
ClaimReview.description:
Schema.org/ClaimReview
A fact-checking review of claims made (or reported) in some creative work (referenced via itemReviewed).
ClaimReview.author: schema.org

Class.name: Class
Class.description:
Schema.org/Class
A class, also often called a 'Type'; equivalent to rdfs:Class.
Class.author: schema.org

Clip.name: Clip
Clip.description:
Schema.org/Clip
A short TV or radio program or a segment/part of a program.
Clip.author: schema.org

Code.name: Code
Code.description:
Schema.org/Code
Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.
Code.author: schema.org

Collection.name: Collection
Collection.description:
www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core/Collection
A meaningful collection of concepts.
Labelled collections can be used where you would like a set of concepts to be displayed under a 'node label' in the hierarchy.
Collection.author: w3.org

CollectionPage.name: CollectionPage
CollectionPage.description:
Schema.org/CollectionPage
Web page type: Collection page.
CollectionPage.author: schema.org

CollegeOrUniversity.name: CollegeOrUniversity
CollegeOrUniversity.description:
Schema.org/CollegeOrUniversity
A college, university, or other third-level educational institution.
CollegeOrUniversity.author: schema.org

ComicCoverArt.name: ComicCoverArt
ComicCoverArt.description:
Schema.org/ComicCoverArt
The artwork on the cover of a comic.
ComicCoverArt.author: schema.org

ComicIssue.name: ComicIssue
ComicIssue.description:
Schema.org/ComicIssue
Individual comic issues are serially published as
		part of a larger series. For the sake of consistency, even one-shot issues
		belong to a series comprised of a single issue. All comic issues can be
		uniquely identified by: the combination of the name and volume number of the
		series to which the issue belongs; the issue number; and the variant
		description of the issue (if any).
ComicIssue.author: schema.org

ComicSeries.name: ComicSeries
ComicSeries.description:
Schema.org/ComicSeries
A sequential publication of comic stories under a
		unifying title, for example "The Amazing Spider-Man" or "Groo the
		Wanderer".
ComicSeries.author: schema.org

ComicStory.name: ComicStory
ComicStory.description:
Schema.org/ComicStory
The term "story" is any indivisible, re-printable
		unit of a comic, including the interior stories, covers, and backmatter. Most
		comics have at least two stories: a cover (ComicCoverArt) and an interior story.
ComicStory.author: schema.org

Comment.name: Comment
Comment.description:
Schema.org/Comment
A comment on an item - for example, a comment on a blog post. The comment's content is expressed via the [[text]] property, and its topic via [[about]], properties shared with all CreativeWorks.
Comment.author: schema.org

CommentAction.name: CommentAction
CommentAction.description:
Schema.org/CommentAction
The act of generating a comment about a subject.
CommentAction.author: schema.org

CommunicateAction.name: CommunicateAction
CommunicateAction.description:
Schema.org/CommunicateAction
The act of conveying information to another person via a communication medium (instrument) such as speech, email, or telephone conversation.
CommunicateAction.author: schema.org

CompleteDataFeed.name: CompleteDataFeed
CompleteDataFeed.description:
Schema.org/CompleteDataFeed
A [[CompleteDataFeed]] is a [[DataFeed]] whose standard representation includes content for every item currently in the feed.

This is the equivalent of Atom's element as defined in Feed Paging and Archiving [RFC 5005](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5005), For example (and as defined for Atom), when using data from a feed that represents a collection of items that varies over time (e.g. "Top Twenty Records") there is no need to have newer entries mixed in alongside older, obsolete entries. By marking this feed as a CompleteDataFeed, old entries can be safely discarded when the feed is refreshed, since we can assume the feed has provided descriptions for all current items.
CompleteDataFeed.author: schema.org

CompoundPriceSpecification.name: CompoundPriceSpecification
CompoundPriceSpecification.description:
Schema.org/CompoundPriceSpecification
A compound price specification is one that bundles multiple prices that all apply in combination for different dimensions of consumption. Use the name property of the attached unit price specification for indicating the dimension of a price component (e.g. "electricity" or "final cleaning").
CompoundPriceSpecification.author: schema.org

ComputerLanguage.name: ComputerLanguage
ComputerLanguage.description:
Schema.org/ComputerLanguage
This type covers computer programming languages such as Scheme and Lisp, as well as other language-like computer representations. Natural languages are best represented with the [[Language]] type.
ComputerLanguage.author: schema.org

ConfirmAction.name: ConfirmAction
ConfirmAction.description:
Schema.org/ConfirmAction
The act of notifying someone that a future event/action is going to happen as expected.

Related actions:

* [[CancelAction]]: The antonym of ConfirmAction.
ConfirmAction.author: schema.org

Consortium.name: Consortium
Consortium.description:
Schema.org/Consortium
A Consortium is a membership [[Organization]] whose members are typically Organizations.
Consortium.author: schema.org

ConsumeAction.name: ConsumeAction
ConsumeAction.description:
Schema.org/ConsumeAction
The act of ingesting information/resources/food.
ConsumeAction.author: schema.org

ContactPage.name: ContactPage
ContactPage.description:
Schema.org/ContactPage
Web page type: Contact page.
ContactPage.author: schema.org

ContactPointOption.name: ContactPointOption
ContactPointOption.description:
Schema.org/ContactPointOption
Enumerated options related to a ContactPoint.
ContactPointOption.author: schema.org

Continent.name: Continent
Continent.description:
Schema.org/Continent
One of the continents (for example, Europe or Africa).
Continent.author: schema.org

ControlAction.name: ControlAction
ControlAction.description:
Schema.org/ControlAction
An agent controls a device or application.
ControlAction.author: schema.org

Conversation.name: Conversation
Conversation.description:
Schema.org/Conversation
One or more messages between organizations or people on a particular topic. Individual messages can be linked to the conversation with isPartOf or hasPart properties.
Conversation.author: schema.org

CookAction.name: CookAction
CookAction.description:
Schema.org/CookAction
The act of producing/preparing food.
CookAction.author: schema.org

CourseInstance.name: CourseInstance
CourseInstance.description:
Schema.org/CourseInstance
An instance of a [[Course]] which is distinct from other instances because it is offered at a different time or location or through different media or modes of study or to a specific section of students.
CourseInstance.author: schema.org

CoverArt.name: CoverArt
CoverArt.description:
Schema.org/CoverArt
The artwork on the outer surface of a CreativeWork.
CoverArt.author: schema.org

CovidTestingFacility.name: CovidTestingFacility
CovidTestingFacility.description:
Schema.org/CovidTestingFacility
A CovidTestingFacility is a [[MedicalClinic]] where testing for the COVID-19 Coronavirus
     disease is available. If the facility is being made available from an established [[Pharmacy]], [[Hotel]], or other
     non-medical organization, multiple types can be listed. This makes it easier to re-use existing schema.org information
     about that place e.g. contact info, address, opening hours. Note that in an emergency, such information may not always be reliable.
CovidTestingFacility.author: schema.org

CreateAction.name: CreateAction
CreateAction.description:
Schema.org/CreateAction
The act of deliberately creating/producing/generating/building a result out of the agent.
CreateAction.author: schema.org

CreativeWork.name: CreativeWork
CreativeWork.description:
Schema.org/CreativeWork
The most generic kind of creative work, including books, movies, photographs, software programs, etc.
CreativeWork.author: schema.org

CreativeWorkSeason.name: CreativeWorkSeason
CreativeWorkSeason.description:
Schema.org/CreativeWorkSeason
A media season e.g. tv, radio, video game etc.
CreativeWorkSeason.author: schema.org

CreativeWorkSeries.name: CreativeWorkSeries
CreativeWorkSeries.description:
Schema.org/CreativeWorkSeries
A CreativeWorkSeries in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. CreativeWorkSeries are usually organized into some order, often chronological. Unlike [[ItemList]] which is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e.g. books and periodicals, or media such as tv, radio and games).

Specific subtypes are available for describing [[TVSeries]], [[RadioSeries]], [[MovieSeries]], [[BookSeries]], [[Periodical]] and [[VideoGameSeries]]. In each case, the [[hasPart]] / [[isPartOf]] properties can be used to relate the CreativeWorkSeries to its parts. The general CreativeWorkSeries type serves largely just to organize these more specific and practical subtypes.

It is common for properties applicable to an item from the series to be usefully applied to the containing group. Schema.org attempts to anticipate some of these cases, but publishers should be free to apply properties of the series parts to the series as a whole wherever they seem appropriate.
CreativeWorkSeries.author: schema.org

CreditCard.name: CreditCard
CreditCard.description:
Schema.org/CreditCard
A card payment method of a particular brand or name.  Used to mark up a particular payment method and/or the financial product/service that supplies the card account.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#AmericanExpress
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DinersClub
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Discover
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#JCB
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#MasterCard
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#VISA
CreditCard.author: schema.org

CriticReview.name: CriticReview
CriticReview.description:
Schema.org/CriticReview
A [[CriticReview]] is a more specialized form of Review written or published by a source that is recognized for its reviewing activities. These can include online columns, travel and food guides, TV and radio shows, blogs and other independent Web sites. [[CriticReview]]s are typically more in-depth and professionally written. For simpler, casually written user/visitor/viewer/customer reviews, it is more appropriate to use the [[UserReview]] type. Review aggregator sites such as Metacritic already separate out the site's user reviews from selected critic reviews that originate from third-party sources.
CriticReview.author: schema.org

CssSelectorType.name: CssSelectorType
CssSelectorType.description:
Schema.org/CssSelectorType
Text representing a CSS selector.
CssSelectorType.author: schema.org

CurrencyConversionService.name: CurrencyConversionService
CurrencyConversionService.description:
Schema.org/CurrencyConversionService
A service to convert funds from one currency to another currency.
CurrencyConversionService.author: schema.org

DDxElement.name: DDxElement
DDxElement.description:
Schema.org/DDxElement
An alternative, closely-related condition typically considered later in the differential diagnosis process along with the signs that are used to distinguish it.
DDxElement.author: schema.org

DanceEvent.name: DanceEvent
DanceEvent.description:
Schema.org/DanceEvent
Event type: A social dance.
DanceEvent.author: schema.org

DanceGroup.name: DanceGroup
DanceGroup.description:
Schema.org/DanceGroup
A dance group—for example, the Alvin Ailey Dance Theater or Riverdance.
DanceGroup.author: schema.org

DataDownload.name: DataDownload
DataDownload.description:
Schema.org/DataDownload
A dataset in downloadable form.
DataDownload.author: schema.org

DataFeed.name: DataFeed
DataFeed.description:
Schema.org/DataFeed
A single feed providing structured information about one or more entities or topics.
DataFeed.author: schema.org

DataFeedItem.name: DataFeedItem
DataFeedItem.description:
Schema.org/DataFeedItem
A single item within a larger data feed.
DataFeedItem.author: schema.org

Dataset.name: Dataset
Dataset.description:
Schema.org/Dataset
A body of structured information describing some topic(s) of interest.
Dataset.author: schema.org

DatedMoneySpecification.name: DatedMoneySpecification
DatedMoneySpecification.description:
Schema.org/DatedMoneySpecification
A DatedMoneySpecification represents monetary values with optional start and end dates. For example, this could represent an employee's salary over a specific period of time. __Note:__ This type has been superseded by [[MonetaryAmount]] use of that type is recommended
DatedMoneySpecification.author: schema.org

DayOfWeek.name: DayOfWeek
DayOfWeek.description:
Schema.org/DayOfWeek
The day of the week, e.g. used to specify to which day the opening hours of an OpeningHoursSpecification refer.

Originally, URLs from [GoodRelations](http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1) were used (for [[Monday]], [[Tuesday]], [[Wednesday]], [[Thursday]], [[Friday]], [[Saturday]], [[Sunday]] plus a special entry for [[PublicHolidays]]); these have now been integrated directly into schema.org.
DayOfWeek.author: schema.org

DeactivateAction.name: DeactivateAction
DeactivateAction.description:
Schema.org/DeactivateAction
The act of stopping or deactivating a device or application (e.g. stopping a timer or turning off a flashlight).
DeactivateAction.author: schema.org

DefenceEstablishment.name: DefenceEstablishment
DefenceEstablishment.description:
Schema.org/DefenceEstablishment
A defence establishment, such as an army or navy base.
DefenceEstablishment.author: schema.org

DefinedRegion.name: DefinedRegion
DefinedRegion.description:
Schema.org/DefinedRegion
A DefinedRegion is a geographic area defined by potentially arbitrary (rather than political, administrative or natural geographical) criteria. Properties are provided for defining a region by reference to sets of postal codes.

Examples: a delivery destination when shopping. Region where regional pricing is configured.

Requirement 1:
Country: US
States: "NY", "CA"

Requirement 2:
Country: US
PostalCode Set: { [94000-94585], [97000, 97999], [13000, 13599]}
{ [12345, 12345], [78945, 78945], }
Region = state, canton, prefecture, autonomous community...
DefinedRegion.author: schema.org

DefinedTerm.name: DefinedTerm
DefinedTerm.description:
Schema.org/DefinedTerm
A word, name, acronym, phrase, etc. with a formal definition. Often used in the context of category or subject classification, glossaries or dictionaries, product or creative work types, etc. Use the name property for the term being defined, use termCode if the term has an alpha-numeric code allocated, use description to provide the definition of the term.
DefinedTerm.author: schema.org

DefinedTermSet.name: DefinedTermSet
DefinedTermSet.description:
Schema.org/DefinedTermSet
A set of defined terms for example a set of categories or a classification scheme, a glossary, dictionary or enumeration.
DefinedTermSet.author: schema.org

DeleteAction.name: DeleteAction
DeleteAction.description:
Schema.org/DeleteAction
The act of editing a recipient by removing one of its objects.
DeleteAction.author: schema.org

DeliveryChargeSpecification.name: DeliveryChargeSpecification
DeliveryChargeSpecification.description:
Schema.org/DeliveryChargeSpecification
The price for the delivery of an offer using a particular delivery method.
DeliveryChargeSpecification.author: schema.org

DeliveryEvent.name: DeliveryEvent
DeliveryEvent.description:
Schema.org/DeliveryEvent
An event involving the delivery of an item.
DeliveryEvent.author: schema.org

DeliveryMethod.name: DeliveryMethod
DeliveryMethod.description:
Schema.org/DeliveryMethod
A delivery method is a standardized procedure for transferring the product or service to the destination of fulfillment chosen by the customer. Delivery methods are characterized by the means of transportation used, and by the organization or group that is the contracting party for the sending organization or person.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeDirectDownload
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeFreight
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeMail
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeOwnFleet
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModePickUp
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS
DeliveryMethod.author: schema.org

DeliveryTimeSettings.name: DeliveryTimeSettings
DeliveryTimeSettings.description:
Schema.org/DeliveryTimeSettings
A DeliveryTimeSettings represents re-usable pieces of shipping information, relating to timing. It is designed for publication on an URL that may be referenced via the [[shippingSettingsLink]] property of a [[OfferShippingDetails]]. Several occurrences can be published, distinguished (and identified/referenced) by their different values for [[transitTimeLabel]].
DeliveryTimeSettings.author: schema.org

Demand.name: Demand
Demand.description:
Schema.org/Demand
A demand entity represents the public, not necessarily binding, not necessarily exclusive, announcement by an organization or person to seek a certain type of goods or services. For describing demand using this type, the very same properties used for Offer apply.
Demand.author: schema.org

DepartAction.name: DepartAction
DepartAction.description:
Schema.org/DepartAction
The act of  departing from a place. An agent departs from an fromLocation for a destination, optionally with participants.
DepartAction.author: schema.org

DepositAccount.name: DepositAccount
DepositAccount.description:
Schema.org/DepositAccount
A type of Bank Account with a main purpose of depositing funds to gain interest or other benefits.
DepositAccount.author: schema.org

DiagnosticLab.name: DiagnosticLab
DiagnosticLab.description:
Schema.org/DiagnosticLab
A medical laboratory that offers on-site or off-site diagnostic services.
DiagnosticLab.author: schema.org

DiagnosticProcedure.name: DiagnosticProcedure
DiagnosticProcedure.description:
Schema.org/DiagnosticProcedure
A medical procedure intended primarily for diagnostic, as opposed to therapeutic, purposes.
DiagnosticProcedure.author: schema.org

Diet.name: Diet
Diet.description:
Schema.org/Diet
A strategy of regulating the intake of food to achieve or maintain a specific health-related goal.
Diet.author: schema.org

DietarySupplement.name: DietarySupplement
DietarySupplement.description:
Schema.org/DietarySupplement
A product taken by mouth that contains a dietary ingredient intended to supplement the diet. Dietary ingredients may include vitamins, minerals, herbs or other botanicals, amino acids, and substances such as enzymes, organ tissues, glandulars and metabolites.
DietarySupplement.author: schema.org

DigitalDocument.name: DigitalDocument
DigitalDocument.description:
Schema.org/DigitalDocument
An electronic file or document.
DigitalDocument.author: schema.org

DigitalDocumentPermission.name: DigitalDocumentPermission
DigitalDocumentPermission.description:
Schema.org/DigitalDocumentPermission
A permission for a particular person or group to access a particular file.
DigitalDocumentPermission.author: schema.org

DigitalDocumentPermissionType.name: DigitalDocumentPermissionType
DigitalDocumentPermissionType.description:
Schema.org/DigitalDocumentPermissionType
A type of permission which can be granted for accessing a digital document.
DigitalDocumentPermissionType.author: schema.org

DisagreeAction.name: DisagreeAction
DisagreeAction.description:
Schema.org/DisagreeAction
The act of expressing a difference of opinion with the object. An agent disagrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.
DisagreeAction.author: schema.org

DiscoverAction.name: DiscoverAction
DiscoverAction.description:
Schema.org/DiscoverAction
The act of discovering/finding an object.
DiscoverAction.author: schema.org

DiscussionForumPosting.name: DiscussionForumPosting
DiscussionForumPosting.description:
Schema.org/DiscussionForumPosting
A posting to a discussion forum.
DiscussionForumPosting.author: schema.org

DislikeAction.name: DislikeAction
DislikeAction.description:
Schema.org/DislikeAction
The act of expressing a negative sentiment about the object. An agent dislikes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.
DislikeAction.author: schema.org

Distance.name: Distance
Distance.description:
Schema.org/Distance
Properties that take Distances as values are of the form '<Number> <Length unit of measure>'. E.g., '7 ft'.
Distance.author: schema.org

DonateAction.name: DonateAction
DonateAction.description:
Schema.org/DonateAction
The act of providing goods, services, or money without compensation, often for philanthropic reasons.
DonateAction.author: schema.org

DoseSchedule.name: DoseSchedule
DoseSchedule.description:
Schema.org/DoseSchedule
A specific dosing schedule for a drug or supplement.
DoseSchedule.author: schema.org

DownloadAction.name: DownloadAction
DownloadAction.description:
Schema.org/DownloadAction
The act of downloading an object.
DownloadAction.author: schema.org

DrawAction.name: DrawAction
DrawAction.description:
Schema.org/DrawAction
The act of producing a visual/graphical representation of an object, typically with a pen/pencil and paper as instruments.
DrawAction.author: schema.org

Drawing.name: Drawing
Drawing.description:
Schema.org/Drawing
A picture or diagram made with a pencil, pen, or crayon rather than paint.
Drawing.author: schema.org

DrinkAction.name: DrinkAction
DrinkAction.description:
Schema.org/DrinkAction
The act of swallowing liquids.
DrinkAction.author: schema.org

DriveWheelConfigurationValue.name: DriveWheelConfigurationValue
DriveWheelConfigurationValue.description:
Schema.org/DriveWheelConfigurationValue
A value indicating which roadwheels will receive torque.
DriveWheelConfigurationValue.author: schema.org

Drug.name: Drug
Drug.description:
Schema.org/Drug
A chemical or biologic substance, used as a medical therapy, that has a physiological effect on an organism. Here the term drug is used interchangeably with the term medicine although clinical knowledge make a clear difference between them.
Drug.author: schema.org

DrugClass.name: DrugClass
DrugClass.description:
Schema.org/DrugClass
A class of medical drugs, e.g., statins. Classes can represent general pharmacological class, common mechanisms of action, common physiological effects, etc.
DrugClass.author: schema.org

DrugCost.name: DrugCost
DrugCost.description:
Schema.org/DrugCost
The cost per unit of a medical drug. Note that this type is not meant to represent the price in an offer of a drug for sale; see the Offer type for that. This type will typically be used to tag wholesale or average retail cost of a drug, or maximum reimbursable cost. Costs of medical drugs vary widely depending on how and where they are paid for, so while this type captures some of the variables, costs should be used with caution by consumers of this schema's markup.
DrugCost.author: schema.org

DrugCostCategory.name: DrugCostCategory
DrugCostCategory.description:
Schema.org/DrugCostCategory
Enumerated categories of medical drug costs.
DrugCostCategory.author: schema.org

DrugLegalStatus.name: DrugLegalStatus
DrugLegalStatus.description:
Schema.org/DrugLegalStatus
The legal availability status of a medical drug.
DrugLegalStatus.author: schema.org

DrugPregnancyCategory.name: DrugPregnancyCategory
DrugPregnancyCategory.description:
Schema.org/DrugPregnancyCategory
Categories that represent an assessment of the risk of fetal injury due to a drug or pharmaceutical used as directed by the mother during pregnancy.
DrugPregnancyCategory.author: schema.org

DrugPrescriptionStatus.name: DrugPrescriptionStatus
DrugPrescriptionStatus.description:
Schema.org/DrugPrescriptionStatus
Indicates whether this drug is available by prescription or over-the-counter.
DrugPrescriptionStatus.author: schema.org

DrugStrength.name: DrugStrength
DrugStrength.description:
Schema.org/DrugStrength
A specific strength in which a medical drug is available in a specific country.
DrugStrength.author: schema.org

EUEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.name: EUEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
EUEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.description:
Schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
Enumerates the EU energy efficiency classes A-G as well as A+, A++, and A+++ as defined in EU directive 2017/1369.
EUEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.author: schema.org

EatAction.name: EatAction
EatAction.description:
Schema.org/EatAction
The act of swallowing solid objects.
EatAction.author: schema.org

EducationalOccupationalCredential.name: EducationalOccupationalCredential
EducationalOccupationalCredential.description:
Schema.org/EducationalOccupationalCredential
