An educational or occupational credential. A diploma, academic degree, certification, qualification, badge, etc., that may be awarded to a person or other entity that meets the requirements defined by the credentialer.
EducationalOccupationalCredential.author: schema.org

EducationalOccupationalProgram.name: EducationalOccupationalProgram
EducationalOccupationalProgram.description:
Schema.org/EducationalOccupationalProgram
A program offered by an institution which determines the learning progress to achieve an outcome, usually a credential like a degree or certificate. This would define a discrete set of opportunities (e.g., job, courses) that together constitute a program with a clear start, end, set of requirements, and transition to a new occupational opportunity (e.g., a job), or sometimes a higher educational opportunity (e.g., an advanced degree).
EducationalOccupationalProgram.author: schema.org

EmergencyService.name: EmergencyService
EmergencyService.description:
Schema.org/EmergencyService
An emergency service, such as a fire station or ER.
EmergencyService.author: schema.org

EmployeeRole.name: EmployeeRole
EmployeeRole.description:
Schema.org/EmployeeRole
A subclass of OrganizationRole used to describe employee relationships.
EmployeeRole.author: schema.org

EmployerAggregateRating.name: EmployerAggregateRating
EmployerAggregateRating.description:
Schema.org/EmployerAggregateRating
An aggregate rating of an Organization related to its role as an employer.
EmployerAggregateRating.author: schema.org

EmployerReview.name: EmployerReview
EmployerReview.description:
Schema.org/EmployerReview
An [[EmployerReview]] is a review of an [[Organization]] regarding its role as an employer, written by a current or former employee of that organization.
EmployerReview.author: schema.org

EndorsementRating.name: EndorsementRating
EndorsementRating.description:
Schema.org/EndorsementRating
An EndorsementRating is a rating that expresses some level of endorsement, for example inclusion in a "critic's pick" blog, a
"Like" or "+1" on a social network. It can be considered the [[result]] of an [[EndorseAction]] in which the [[object]] of the action is rated positively by
some [[agent]]. As is common elsewhere in schema.org, it is sometimes more useful to describe the results of such an action without explicitly describing the [[Action]].

An [[EndorsementRating]] may be part of a numeric scale or organized system, but this is not required: having an explicit type for indicating a positive,
endorsement rating is particularly useful in the absence of numeric scales as it helps consumers understand that the rating is broadly positive.
EndorsementRating.author: schema.org

Energy.name: Energy
Energy.description:
Schema.org/Energy
Properties that take Energy as values are of the form '<Number> <Energy unit of measure>'.
Energy.author: schema.org

EnergyConsumptionDetails.name: EnergyConsumptionDetails
EnergyConsumptionDetails.description:
Schema.org/EnergyConsumptionDetails
EnergyConsumptionDetails represents information related to the energy efficiency of a product that consumes energy. The information that can be provided is based on international regulations such as for example [EU directive 2017/1369](https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2017/1369/oj) for energy labeling and the [Energy labeling rule](https://www.ftc.gov/enforcement/rules/rulemaking-regulatory-reform-proceedings/energy-water-use-labeling-consumer) under the Energy Policy and Conservation Act (EPCA) in the US.
EnergyConsumptionDetails.author: schema.org

EnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.name: EnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
EnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.description:
Schema.org/EnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
Enumerates energy efficiency levels (also known as "classes" or "ratings") and certifications that are part of several international energy efficiency standards.
EnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.author: schema.org

EnergyStarEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.name: EnergyStarEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
EnergyStarEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.description:
Schema.org/EnergyStarEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
Used to indicate whether a product is EnergyStar certified.
EnergyStarEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.author: schema.org

EngineSpecification.name: EngineSpecification
EngineSpecification.description:
Schema.org/EngineSpecification
Information about the engine of the vehicle. A vehicle can have multiple engines represented by multiple engine specification entities.
EngineSpecification.author: schema.org

EntryPoint.name: EntryPoint
EntryPoint.description:
Schema.org/EntryPoint
An entry point, within some Web-based protocol.
EntryPoint.author: schema.org

Enumeration.name: Enumeration
Enumeration.description:
Schema.org/Enumeration
Lists or enumerations—for example, a list of cuisines or music genres, etc.
Enumeration.author: schema.org

Episode.name: Episode
Episode.description:
Schema.org/Episode
A media episode (e.g. TV, radio, video game) which can be part of a series or season.
Episode.author: schema.org

Event.name: Event
Event.description:
Schema.org/Event
An event happening at a certain time and location, such as a concert, lecture, or festival. Ticketing information may be added via the [[offers]] property. Repeated events may be structured as separate Event objects.
Event.author: schema.org

EventAttendanceModeEnumeration.name: EventAttendanceModeEnumeration
EventAttendanceModeEnumeration.description:
Schema.org/EventAttendanceModeEnumeration
An EventAttendanceModeEnumeration value is one of potentially several modes of organising an event, relating to whether it is online or offline.
EventAttendanceModeEnumeration.author: schema.org

EventReservation.name: EventReservation
EventReservation.description:
Schema.org/EventReservation
A reservation for an event like a concert, sporting event, or lecture.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].
EventReservation.author: schema.org

EventSeries.name: EventSeries
EventSeries.description:
Schema.org/EventSeries
A series of [[Event]]s. Included events can relate with the series using the [[superEvent]] property.

An EventSeries is a collection of events that share some unifying characteristic. For example, "The Olympic Games" is a series, which
is repeated regularly. The "2012 London Olympics" can be presented both as an [[Event]] in the series "Olympic Games", and as an
[[EventSeries]] that included a number of sporting competitions as Events.

The nature of the association between the events in an [[EventSeries]] can vary, but typical examples could
include a thematic event series (e.g. topical meetups or classes), or a series of regular events that share a location, attendee group and/or organizers.

EventSeries has been defined as a kind of Event to make it easy for publishers to use it in an Event context without
worrying about which kinds of series are really event-like enough to call an Event. In general an EventSeries
may seem more Event-like when the period of time is compact and when aspects such as location are fixed, but
it may also sometimes prove useful to describe a longer-term series as an Event.
EventSeries.author: schema.org

EventStatusType.name: EventStatusType
EventStatusType.description:
Schema.org/EventStatusType
EventStatusType is an enumeration type whose instances represent several states that an Event may be in.
EventStatusType.author: schema.org

ExchangeRateSpecification.name: ExchangeRateSpecification
ExchangeRateSpecification.description:
Schema.org/ExchangeRateSpecification
A structured value representing exchange rate.
ExchangeRateSpecification.author: schema.org

ExerciseAction.name: ExerciseAction
ExerciseAction.description:
Schema.org/ExerciseAction
The act of participating in exertive activity for the purposes of improving health and fitness.
ExerciseAction.author: schema.org

ExercisePlan.name: ExercisePlan
ExercisePlan.description:
Schema.org/ExercisePlan
Fitness-related activity designed for a specific health-related purpose, including defined exercise routines as well as activity prescribed by a clinician.
ExercisePlan.author: schema.org

ExhibitionEvent.name: ExhibitionEvent
ExhibitionEvent.description:
Schema.org/ExhibitionEvent
Event type: Exhibition event, e.g. at a museum, library, archive, tradeshow, ...
ExhibitionEvent.author: schema.org

FAQPage.name: FAQPage
FAQPage.description:
Schema.org/FAQPage
A [[FAQPage]] is a [[WebPage]] presenting one or more "[Frequently asked questions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FAQ)" (see also [[QAPage]]).
FAQPage.author: schema.org

FMRadioChannel.name: FMRadioChannel
FMRadioChannel.description:
Schema.org/FMRadioChannel
A radio channel that uses FM.
FMRadioChannel.author: schema.org

FilmAction.name: FilmAction
FilmAction.description:
Schema.org/FilmAction
The act of capturing sound and moving images on film, video, or digitally.
FilmAction.author: schema.org

FinancialProduct.name: FinancialProduct
FinancialProduct.description:
Schema.org/FinancialProduct
A product provided to consumers and businesses by financial institutions such as banks, insurance companies, brokerage firms, consumer finance companies, and investment companies which comprise the financial services industry.
FinancialProduct.author: schema.org

FindAction.name: FindAction
FindAction.description:
Schema.org/FindAction
The act of finding an object.

Related actions:

* [[SearchAction]]: FindAction is generally lead by a SearchAction, but not necessarily.
FindAction.author: schema.org

FireStation.name: FireStation
FireStation.description:
Schema.org/FireStation
A fire station. With firemen.
FireStation.author: schema.org

FlightReservation.name: FlightReservation
FlightReservation.description:
Schema.org/FlightReservation
A reservation for air travel.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].
FlightReservation.author: schema.org

FloorPlan.name: FloorPlan
FloorPlan.description:
Schema.org/FloorPlan
A FloorPlan is an explicit representation of a collection of similar accommodations, allowing the provision of common information (room counts, sizes, layout diagrams) and offers for rental or sale. In typical use, some [[ApartmentComplex]] has an [[accommodationFloorPlan]] which is a [[FloorPlan]].  A FloorPlan is always in the context of a particular place, either a larger [[ApartmentComplex]] or a single [[Apartment]]. The visual/spatial aspects of a floor plan (i.e. room layout, [see wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floor_plan)) can be indicated using [[image]].
FloorPlan.author: schema.org

FollowAction.name: FollowAction
FollowAction.description:
Schema.org/FollowAction
The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates polled from.

Related actions:

* [[BefriendAction]]: Unlike BefriendAction, FollowAction implies that the connection is *not* necessarily reciprocal.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, FollowAction implies that the follower acts as an active agent constantly/actively polling for updates.
* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in continuing receiving updates from the object.
* [[JoinAction]]: Unlike JoinAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in getting updates from the object.
* [[TrackAction]]: Unlike TrackAction, FollowAction refers to the polling of updates of all aspects of animate objects rather than the location of inanimate objects (e.g. you track a package, but you don't follow it).
FollowAction.author: schema.org

FoodEstablishmentReservation.name: FoodEstablishmentReservation
FoodEstablishmentReservation.description:
Schema.org/FoodEstablishmentReservation
A reservation to dine at a food-related business.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.
FoodEstablishmentReservation.author: schema.org

FoodService.name: FoodService
FoodService.description:
Schema.org/FoodService
A food service, like breakfast, lunch, or dinner.
FoodService.author: schema.org

FundingAgency.name: FundingAgency
FundingAgency.description:
Schema.org/FundingAgency
A FundingAgency is an organization that implements one or more [[FundingScheme]]s and manages
   the granting process (via [[Grant]]s, typically [[MonetaryGrant]]s).
   A funding agency is not always required for grant funding, e.g. philanthropic giving, corporate sponsorship etc.

Examples of funding agencies include ERC, REA, NIH, Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation...
FundingAgency.author: schema.org

FundingScheme.name: FundingScheme
FundingScheme.description:
Schema.org/FundingScheme
A FundingScheme combines organizational, project and policy aspects of grant-based funding
   that sets guidelines, principles and mechanisms to support other kinds of projects and activities.
   Funding is typically organized via [[Grant]] funding. Examples of funding schemes: Swiss Priority Programmes (SPPs); EU Framework 7 (FP7); Horizon 2020; the NIH-R01 Grant Program; Wellcome institutional strategic support fund. For large scale public sector funding, the management and administration of grant awards is often handled by other, dedicated, organizations - [[FundingAgency]]s such as ERC, REA, ...
FundingScheme.author: schema.org

Game.name: Game
Game.description:
Schema.org/Game
The Game type represents things which are games. These are typically rule-governed recreational activities, e.g. role-playing games in which players assume the role of characters in a fictional setting.
Game.author: schema.org

GamePlayMode.name: GamePlayMode
GamePlayMode.description:
Schema.org/GamePlayMode
Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.
GamePlayMode.author: schema.org

GameServer.name: GameServer
GameServer.description:
Schema.org/GameServer
Server that provides game interaction in a multiplayer game.
GameServer.author: schema.org

GameServerStatus.name: GameServerStatus
GameServerStatus.description:
Schema.org/GameServerStatus
Status of a game server.
GameServerStatus.author: schema.org

GeoCircle.name: GeoCircle
GeoCircle.description:
Schema.org/GeoCircle
A GeoCircle is a GeoShape representing a circular geographic area. As it is a GeoShape
         it provides the simple textual property 'circle', but also allows the combination of postalCode alongside geoRadius.
         The center of the circle can be indicated via the 'geoMidpoint' property, or more approximately using 'address', 'postalCode'.
GeoCircle.author: schema.org

GeoShape.name: GeoShape
GeoShape.description:
Schema.org/GeoShape
The geographic shape of a place. A GeoShape can be described using several properties whose values are based on latitude/longitude pairs. Either whitespace or commas can be used to separate latitude and longitude; whitespace should be used when writing a list of several such points.
GeoShape.author: schema.org

GeospatialGeometry.name: GeospatialGeometry
GeospatialGeometry.description:
Schema.org/GeospatialGeometry
(Eventually to be defined as) a supertype of GeoShape designed to accommodate definitions from Geo-Spatial best practices.
GeospatialGeometry.author: schema.org

GiveAction.name: GiveAction
GiveAction.description:
Schema.org/GiveAction
The act of transferring ownership of an object to a destination. Reciprocal of TakeAction.

Related actions:

* [[TakeAction]]: Reciprocal of GiveAction.
* [[SendAction]]: Unlike SendAction, GiveAction implies that ownership is being transferred (e.g. I may send my laptop to you, but that doesn't mean I'm giving it to you).
GiveAction.author: schema.org

GovernmentBenefitsType.name: GovernmentBenefitsType
GovernmentBenefitsType.description:
Schema.org/GovernmentBenefitsType
GovernmentBenefitsType enumerates several kinds of government benefits to support the COVID-19 situation. Note that this structure may not capture all benefits offered.
GovernmentBenefitsType.author: schema.org

GovernmentOffice.name: GovernmentOffice
GovernmentOffice.description:
Schema.org/GovernmentOffice
A government office—for example, an IRS or DMV office.
GovernmentOffice.author: schema.org

GovernmentOrganization.name: GovernmentOrganization
GovernmentOrganization.description:
Schema.org/GovernmentOrganization
A governmental organization or agency.
GovernmentOrganization.author: schema.org

GovernmentPermit.name: GovernmentPermit
GovernmentPermit.description:
Schema.org/GovernmentPermit
A permit issued by a government agency.
GovernmentPermit.author: schema.org

GovernmentService.name: GovernmentService
GovernmentService.description:
Schema.org/GovernmentService
A service provided by a government organization, e.g. food stamps, veterans benefits, etc.
GovernmentService.author: schema.org

Grant.name: Grant
Grant.description:
Schema.org/Grant
A grant, typically financial or otherwise quantifiable, of resources. Typically a [[funder]] sponsors some [[MonetaryAmount]] to an [[Organization]] or [[Person]],
   sometimes not necessarily via a dedicated or long-lived [[Project]], resulting in one or more outputs, or [[fundedItem]]s. For financial sponsorship, indicate the [[funder]] of a [[MonetaryGrant]]. For non-financial support, indicate [[sponsor]] of [[Grant]]s of resources (e.g. office space).

Grants support  activities directed towards some agreed collective goals, often but not always organized as [[Project]]s. Long-lived projects are sometimes sponsored by a variety of grants over time, but it is also common for a project to be associated with a single grant.

The amount of a [[Grant]] is represented using [[amount]] as a [[MonetaryAmount]].
Grant.author: schema.org

Guide.name: Guide
Guide.description:
Schema.org/Guide
[[Guide]] is a page or article that recommend specific products or services, or aspects of a thing for a user to consider. A [[Guide]] may represent a Buying Guide and detail aspects of products or services for a user to consider. A [[Guide]] may represent a Product Guide and recommend specific products or services. A [[Guide]] may represent a Ranked List and recommend specific products or services with ranking.
Guide.author: schema.org

HVACBusiness.name: HVACBusiness
HVACBusiness.description:
Schema.org/HVACBusiness
A business that provide Heating, Ventilation and Air Conditioning services.
HVACBusiness.author: schema.org

HealthAspectEnumeration.name: HealthAspectEnumeration
HealthAspectEnumeration.description:
Schema.org/HealthAspectEnumeration
HealthAspectEnumeration enumerates several aspects of health content online, each of which might be described using [[hasHealthAspect]] and [[HealthTopicContent]].
HealthAspectEnumeration.author: schema.org

HealthInsurancePlan.name: HealthInsurancePlan
HealthInsurancePlan.description:
Schema.org/HealthInsurancePlan
A US-style health insurance plan, including PPOs, EPOs, and HMOs.
HealthInsurancePlan.author: schema.org

HealthPlanCostSharingSpecification.name: HealthPlanCostSharingSpecification
HealthPlanCostSharingSpecification.description:
Schema.org/HealthPlanCostSharingSpecification
A description of costs to the patient under a given network or formulary.
HealthPlanCostSharingSpecification.author: schema.org

HealthPlanFormulary.name: HealthPlanFormulary
HealthPlanFormulary.description:
Schema.org/HealthPlanFormulary
For a given health insurance plan, the specification for costs and coverage of prescription drugs.
HealthPlanFormulary.author: schema.org

HealthPlanNetwork.name: HealthPlanNetwork
HealthPlanNetwork.description:
Schema.org/HealthPlanNetwork
A US-style health insurance plan network.
HealthPlanNetwork.author: schema.org

HealthTopicContent.name: HealthTopicContent
HealthTopicContent.description:
Schema.org/HealthTopicContent
[[HealthTopicContent]] is [[WebContent]] that is about some aspect of a health topic, e.g. a condition, its symptoms or treatments. Such content may be comprised of several parts or sections and use different types of media. Multiple instances of [[WebContent]] (and hence [[HealthTopicContent]]) can be related using [[hasPart]] / [[isPartOf]] where there is some kind of content hierarchy, and their content described with [[about]] and [[mentions]] e.g. building upon the existing [[MedicalCondition]] vocabulary.
HealthTopicContent.author: schema.org

HobbyShop.name: HobbyShop
HobbyShop.description:
Schema.org/HobbyShop
A store that sells materials useful or necessary for various hobbies.
HobbyShop.author: schema.org

HomeAndConstructionBusiness.name: HomeAndConstructionBusiness
HomeAndConstructionBusiness.description:
Schema.org/HomeAndConstructionBusiness
A construction business.

A HomeAndConstructionBusiness is a [[LocalBusiness]] that provides services around homes and buildings.

As a [[LocalBusiness]] it can be described as a [[provider]] of one or more [[Service]]\(s).
HomeAndConstructionBusiness.author: schema.org

Hostel.name: Hostel
Hostel.description:
Schema.org/Hostel A hostel - cheap accommodation, often in shared dormitories.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
Hostel.author: schema.org

Hotel.name: Hotel
Hotel.description:
Schema.org/Hotel A hotel is an establishment that provides lodging paid on a short-term basis (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hotel).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
Hotel.author: schema.org

HotelRoom.name: HotelRoom
HotelRoom.description:
Schema.org/HotelRoom A hotel room is a single room in a hotel.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
HotelRoom.author: schema.org

House.name: House
House.description: Schema.org/House A house is a building or structure that has the ability to be occupied for habitation by humans or other creatures (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House).
House.author: schema.org

HowTo.name: HowTo
HowTo.description:
Schema.org/HowTo
Instructions that explain how to achieve a result by performing a sequence of steps.
HowTo.author: schema.org

HowToDirection.name: HowToDirection
HowToDirection.description:
Schema.org/HowToDirection
A direction indicating a single action to do in the instructions for how to achieve a result.
HowToDirection.author: schema.org

HowToItem.name: HowToItem
HowToItem.description:
Schema.org/HowToItem
An item used as either a tool or supply when performing the instructions for how to to achieve a result.
HowToItem.author: schema.org

HowToSection.name: HowToSection
HowToSection.description:
Schema.org/HowToSection
A sub-grouping of steps in the instructions for how to achieve a result (e.g. steps for making a pie crust within a pie recipe).
HowToSection.author: schema.org

HowToStep.name: HowToStep
HowToStep.description:
Schema.org/HowToStep
A step in the instructions for how to achieve a result. It is an ordered list with HowToDirection and/or HowToTip items.
HowToStep.author: schema.org

HowToSupply.name: HowToSupply
HowToSupply.description:
Schema.org/HowToSupply
A supply consumed when performing the instructions for how to achieve a result.
HowToSupply.author: schema.org

HowToTip.name: HowToTip
HowToTip.description:
Schema.org/HowToTip
An explanation in the instructions for how to achieve a result. It provides supplementary information about a technique, supply, author's preference, etc. It can explain what could be done, or what should not be done, but doesn't specify what should be done (see HowToDirection).
HowToTip.author: schema.org

HowToTool.name: HowToTool
HowToTool.description:
Schema.org/HowToTool
A tool used (but not consumed) when performing instructions for how to achieve a result.
HowToTool.author: schema.org

HyperToc.name: HyperToc
HyperToc.description:
Schema.org/HyperToc
A HyperToc represents a hypertext table of contents for complex media objects, such as [[VideoObject]], [[AudioObject]]. Items in the table of contents are indicated using the [[tocEntry]] property, and typed [[HyperTocEntry]]. For cases where the same larger work is split into multiple files, [[associatedMedia]] can be used on individual [[HyperTocEntry]] items.
HyperToc.author: schema.org

HyperTocEntry.name: HyperTocEntry
HyperTocEntry.description:
Schema.org/HyperTocEntry
A HyperToEntry is an item within a [[HyperToc]], which represents a hypertext table of contents for complex media objects, such as [[VideoObject]], [[AudioObject]]. The media object itself is indicated using [[associatedMedia]]. Each section of interest within that content can be described with a [[HyperTocEntry]], with associated [[startOffset]] and [[endOffset]]. When several entries are all from the same file, [[associatedMedia]] is used on the overarching [[HyperTocEntry]]; if the content has been split into multiple files, they can be referenced using [[associatedMedia]] on each [[HyperTocEntry]].
HyperTocEntry.author: schema.org

IgnoreAction.name: IgnoreAction
IgnoreAction.description:
Schema.org/IgnoreAction
The act of intentionally disregarding the object. An agent ignores an object.
IgnoreAction.author: schema.org

ImageGallery.name: ImageGallery
ImageGallery.description:
Schema.org/ImageGallery
Web page type: Image gallery page.
ImageGallery.author: schema.org

ImagingTest.name: ImagingTest
ImagingTest.description:
Schema.org/ImagingTest
Any medical imaging modality typically used for diagnostic purposes.
ImagingTest.author: schema.org

IndividualProduct.name: IndividualProduct
IndividualProduct.description:
Schema.org/IndividualProduct
A single, identifiable product instance (e.g. a laptop with a particular serial number).
IndividualProduct.author: schema.org

InfectiousAgentClass.name: InfectiousAgentClass
InfectiousAgentClass.description:
Schema.org/InfectiousAgentClass
Classes of agents or pathogens that transmit infectious diseases. Enumerated type.
InfectiousAgentClass.author: schema.org

InfectiousDisease.name: InfectiousDisease
InfectiousDisease.description:
Schema.org/InfectiousDisease
An infectious disease is a clinically evident human disease resulting from the presence of pathogenic microbial agents, like pathogenic viruses, pathogenic bacteria, fungi, protozoa, multicellular parasites, and prions. To be considered an infectious disease, such pathogens are known to be able to cause this disease.
InfectiousDisease.author: schema.org

InformAction.name: InformAction
InformAction.description:
Schema.org/InformAction
The act of notifying someone of information pertinent to them, with no expectation of a response.
InformAction.author: schema.org

InsertAction.name: InsertAction
InsertAction.description:
Schema.org/InsertAction
The act of adding at a specific location in an ordered collection.
InsertAction.author: schema.org

InstallAction.name: InstallAction
InstallAction.description:
Schema.org/InstallAction
The act of installing an application.
InstallAction.author: schema.org

Intangible.name: Intangible
Intangible.description:
Schema.org/Intangible
A utility class that serves as the umbrella for a number of 'intangible' things such as quantities, structured values, etc.
Intangible.author: schema.org

InteractAction.name: InteractAction
InteractAction.description:
Schema.org/InteractAction
The act of interacting with another person or organization.
InteractAction.author: schema.org

InteractionCounter.name: InteractionCounter
InteractionCounter.description:
Schema.org/InteractionCounter
A summary of how users have interacted with this CreativeWork. In most cases, authors will use a subtype to specify the specific type of interaction.
InteractionCounter.author: schema.org

InvestmentFund.name: InvestmentFund
InvestmentFund.description:
Schema.org/InvestmentFund
A company or fund that gathers capital from a number of investors to create a pool of money that is then re-invested into stocks, bonds and other assets.
InvestmentFund.author: schema.org

InvestmentOrDeposit.name: InvestmentOrDeposit
InvestmentOrDeposit.description:
Schema.org/InvestmentOrDeposit
A type of financial product that typically requires the client to transfer funds to a financial service in return for potential beneficial financial return.
InvestmentOrDeposit.author: schema.org

InviteAction.name: InviteAction
InviteAction.description:
Schema.org/InviteAction
The act of asking someone to attend an event. Reciprocal of RsvpAction.
InviteAction.author: schema.org

Invoice.name: Invoice
Invoice.description:
Schema.org/Invoice
A statement of the money due for goods or services; a bill.
Invoice.author: schema.org

ItemAvailability.name: ItemAvailability
ItemAvailability.description:
Schema.org/ItemAvailability
A list of possible product availability options.
ItemAvailability.author: schema.org

ItemList.name: ItemList
ItemList.description:
Schema.org/ItemList
A list of items of any sort—for example, Top 10 Movies About Weathermen, or Top 100 Party Songs. Not to be confused with HTML lists, which are often used only for formatting.
ItemList.author: schema.org

ItemListOrderType.name: ItemListOrderType
ItemListOrderType.description:
Schema.org/ItemListOrderType
Enumerated for values for itemListOrder for indicating how an ordered ItemList is organized.
ItemListOrderType.author: schema.org

ItemPage.name: ItemPage
ItemPage.description:
Schema.org/ItemPage
A page devoted to a single item, such as a particular product or hotel.
ItemPage.author: schema.org

JobPosting.name: JobPosting
JobPosting.description:
Schema.org/JobPosting
A listing that describes a job opening in a certain organization.
JobPosting.author: schema.org

JoinAction.name: JoinAction
JoinAction.description:
Schema.org/JoinAction
An agent joins an event/group with participants/friends at a location.

Related actions:

* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, JoinAction refers to joining a group/team of people.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, JoinAction does not imply that you'll be receiving updates.
* [[FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, JoinAction does not imply that you'll be polling for updates.
JoinAction.author: schema.org

Joint.name: Joint
Joint.description:
Schema.org/Joint
The anatomical location at which two or more bones make contact.
Joint.author: schema.org

LakeBodyOfWater.name: LakeBodyOfWater
LakeBodyOfWater.description:
Schema.org/LakeBodyOfWater
A lake (for example, Lake Pontrachain).
LakeBodyOfWater.author: schema.org

Landform.name: Landform
Landform.description:
Schema.org/Landform
A landform or physical feature.  Landform elements include mountains, plains, lakes, rivers, seascape and oceanic waterbody interface features such as bays, peninsulas, seas and so forth, including sub-aqueous terrain features such as submersed mountain ranges, volcanoes, and the great ocean basins.
Landform.author: schema.org

LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings.name: LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings
LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings.description:
Schema.org/LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings
An historical landmark or building.
LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings.author: schema.org

Language.name: Language
Language.description:
Schema.org/Language
Natural languages such as Spanish, Tamil, Hindi, English, etc. Formal language code tags expressed in [BCP 47](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IETF_language_tag) can be used via the [[alternateName]] property. The Language type previously also covered programming languages such as Scheme and Lisp, which are now best represented using [[ComputerLanguage]].
Language.author: schema.org

LeaveAction.name: LeaveAction
LeaveAction.description:
Schema.org/LeaveAction
An agent leaves an event / group with participants/friends at a location.

Related actions:

* [[JoinAction]]: The antonym of LeaveAction.
* [[UnRegisterAction]]: Unlike UnRegisterAction, LeaveAction implies leaving a group/team of people rather than a service.
LeaveAction.author: schema.org

LegalForceStatus.name: LegalForceStatus
LegalForceStatus.description:
Schema.org/LegalForceStatus
A list of possible statuses for the legal force of a legislation.
LegalForceStatus.author: schema.org

LegalService.name: LegalService
LegalService.description:
Schema.org/LegalService
A LegalService is a business that provides legally-oriented services, advice and representation, e.g. law firms.\n\nAs a [[LocalBusiness]] it can be described as a [[provider]] of one or more [[Service]]\(s).
LegalService.author: schema.org

LegalValueLevel.name: LegalValueLevel
LegalValueLevel.description:
Schema.org/LegalValueLevel
A list of possible levels for the legal validity of a legislation.
LegalValueLevel.author: schema.org

Legislation.name: Legislation
Legislation.description:
Schema.org/Legislation
A legal document such as an act, decree, bill, etc. (enforceable or not) or a component of a legal act (like an article).
Legislation.author: schema.org

LegislationObject.name: LegislationObject
LegislationObject.description:
Schema.org/LegislationObject
A specific object or file containing a Legislation. Note that the same Legislation can be published in multiple files. For example, a digitally signed PDF, a plain PDF and an HTML version.
LegislationObject.author: schema.org

LegislativeBuilding.name: LegislativeBuilding
LegislativeBuilding.description:
Schema.org/LegislativeBuilding
A legislative building—for example, the state capitol.
LegislativeBuilding.author: schema.org

LendAction.name: LendAction
LendAction.description:
Schema.org/LendAction
The act of providing an object under an agreement that it will be returned at a later date. Reciprocal of BorrowAction.

Related actions:

* [[BorrowAction]]: Reciprocal of LendAction.
LendAction.author: schema.org

LibrarySystem.name: LibrarySystem
LibrarySystem.description:
Schema.org/LibrarySystem
A [[LibrarySystem]] is a collaborative system amongst several libraries.
LibrarySystem.author: schema.org

LifestyleModification.name: LifestyleModification
LifestyleModification.description:
Schema.org/LifestyleModification
A process of care involving exercise, changes to diet, fitness routines, and other lifestyle changes aimed at improving a health condition.
LifestyleModification.author: schema.org

Ligament.name: Ligament
Ligament.description:
Schema.org/Ligament
A short band of tough, flexible, fibrous connective tissue that functions to connect multiple bones, cartilages, and structurally support joints.
Ligament.author: schema.org

LikeAction.name: LikeAction
LikeAction.description:
Schema.org/LikeAction
The act of expressing a positive sentiment about the object. An agent likes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.
LikeAction.author: schema.org

LinkRole.name: LinkRole
LinkRole.description:
Schema.org/LinkRole
A Role that represents a Web link e.g. as expressed via the 'url' property. Its linkRelationship property can indicate URL-based and plain textual link types e.g. those in IANA link registry or others such as 'amphtml'. This structure provides a placeholder where details from HTML's link element can be represented outside of HTML, e.g. in JSON-LD feeds.
LinkRole.author: schema.org

LiquorStore.name: LiquorStore
LiquorStore.description:
Schema.org/LiquorStore
A shop that sells alcoholic drinks such as wine, beer, whisky and other spirits.
LiquorStore.author: schema.org

ListItem.name: ListItem
ListItem.description:
Schema.org/ListItem
An list item, e.g. a step in a checklist or how-to description.
ListItem.author: schema.org

ListenAction.name: ListenAction
ListenAction.description:
Schema.org/ListenAction
The act of consuming audio content.
ListenAction.author: schema.org

LiveBlogPosting.name: LiveBlogPosting
LiveBlogPosting.description:
Schema.org/LiveBlogPosting
A blog post intended to provide a rolling textual coverage of an ongoing event through continuous updates.
LiveBlogPosting.author: schema.org

LoanOrCredit.name: LoanOrCredit
LoanOrCredit.description:
Schema.org/LoanOrCredit
A financial product for the loaning of an amount of money, or line of credit, under agreed terms and charges.
LoanOrCredit.author: schema.org

LocalBusiness.name: LocalBusiness
LocalBusiness.description:
Schema.org/LocalBusiness
A particular physical business or branch of an organization. Examples of LocalBusiness include a restaurant, a particular branch of a restaurant chain, a branch of a bank, a medical practice, a club, a bowling alley, etc.
LocalBusiness.author: schema.org

LocationFeatureSpecification.name: LocationFeatureSpecification
LocationFeatureSpecification.description:
Schema.org/LocationFeatureSpecification
Specifies a location feature by providing a structured value representing a feature of an accommodation as a property-value pair of varying degrees of formality.
LocationFeatureSpecification.author: schema.org

LodgingBusiness.name: LodgingBusiness
LodgingBusiness.description:
Schema.org/LodgingBusiness
A lodging business, such as a motel, hotel, or inn.
LodgingBusiness.author: schema.org

LodgingReservation.name: LodgingReservation
LodgingReservation.description:
Schema.org/LodgingReservation
A reservation for lodging at a hotel, motel, inn, etc.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.
LodgingReservation.author: schema.org

LoseAction.name: LoseAction
LoseAction.description:
Schema.org/LoseAction
The act of being defeated in a competitive activity.
LoseAction.author: schema.org

LymphaticVessel.name: LymphaticVessel
LymphaticVessel.description:
Schema.org/LymphaticVessel
A type of blood vessel that specifically carries lymph fluid unidirectionally toward the heart.
LymphaticVessel.author: schema.org

Manuscript.name: Manuscript
Manuscript.description:
Schema.org/Manuscript
A book, document, or piece of music written by hand rather than typed or printed.
Manuscript.author: schema.org

MapCategoryType.name: MapCategoryType
MapCategoryType.description:
Schema.org/MapCategoryType
An enumeration of several kinds of Map.
MapCategoryType.author: schema.org

MarryAction.name: MarryAction
MarryAction.description:
Schema.org/MarryAction
The act of marrying a person.
MarryAction.author: schema.org

Mass.name: Mass
Mass.description:
Schema.org/Mass
Properties that take Mass as values are of the form '<Number> <Mass unit of measure>'. E.g., '7 kg'.
Mass.author: schema.org

MathSolver.name: MathSolver
MathSolver.description:
Schema.org/MathSolver
A math solver which is capable of solving a subset of mathematical problems.
MathSolver.author: schema.org

MaximumDoseSchedule.name: MaximumDoseSchedule
MaximumDoseSchedule.description:
Schema.org/MaximumDoseSchedule
The maximum dosing schedule considered safe for a drug or supplement as recommended by an authority or by the drug/supplement's manufacturer. Capture the recommending authority in the recognizingAuthority property of MedicalEntity.
MaximumDoseSchedule.author: schema.org

MeasurementTypeEnumeration.name: MeasurementTypeEnumeration
MeasurementTypeEnumeration.description:
Schema.org/MeasurementTypeEnumeration
Enumeration of common measurement types (or dimensions), for example "chest" for a person, "inseam" for pants, "gauge" for screws, or "wheel" for bicycles.
MeasurementTypeEnumeration.author: schema.org

MediaGallery.name: MediaGallery
MediaGallery.description:
Schema.org/MediaGallery
Web page type: Media gallery page. A mixed-media page that can contains media such as images, videos, and other multimedia.
MediaGallery.author: schema.org

MediaManipulationRatingEnumeration.name: MediaManipulationRatingEnumeration
MediaManipulationRatingEnumeration.description:
Schema.org/MediaManipulationRatingEnumeration
 Codes for use with the [[mediaAuthenticityCategory]] property, indicating the authenticity of a media object (in the context of how it was published or shared). In general these codes are not mutually exclusive, although some combinations (such as 'original' versus 'transformed', 'edited' and 'staged') would be contradictory if applied in the same [[MediaReview]]. Note that the application of these codes is with regard to a piece of media shared or published in a particular context.
MediaManipulationRatingEnumeration.author: schema.org

MediaObject.name: MediaObject
MediaObject.description:
Schema.org/MediaObject
A media object, such as an image, video, or audio object embedded in a web page or a downloadable dataset i.e. DataDownload. Note that a creative work may have many media objects associated with it on the same web page. For example, a page about a single song (MusicRecording) may have a music video (VideoObject), and a high and low bandwidth audio stream (2 AudioObject's).
MediaObject.author: schema.org

MediaReview.name: MediaReview
MediaReview.description:
Schema.org/MediaReview
A [[MediaReview]] is a more specialized form of Review dedicated to the evaluation of media content online, typically in the context of fact-checking and misinformation.
   For more general reviews of media in the broader sense, use [[UserReview]], [[CriticReview]] or other [[Review]] types. This definition is
   a work in progress. While the [[MediaManipulationRatingEnumeration]] list reflects significant community review amongst fact-checkers and others working
   to combat misinformation, the specific structures for representing media objects, their versions and publication context, is still evolving. Similarly, best practices for the relationship between [[MediaReview]] and [[ClaimReview]] markup has not yet been finalized.
MediaReview.author: schema.org

MediaSubscription.name: MediaSubscription
MediaSubscription.description:
Schema.org/MediaSubscription
A subscription which allows a user to access media including audio, video, books, etc.
MediaSubscription.author: schema.org

MedicalAudience.name: MedicalAudience
MedicalAudience.description:
Schema.org/MedicalAudience
Target audiences for medical web pages.
MedicalAudience.author: schema.org

MedicalAudienceType.name: MedicalAudienceType
MedicalAudienceType.description:
Schema.org/MedicalAudienceType
Target audiences types for medical web pages. Enumerated type.
MedicalAudienceType.author: schema.org

MedicalBusiness.name: MedicalBusiness
MedicalBusiness.description:
Schema.org/MedicalBusiness
A particular physical or virtual business of an organization for medical purposes. Examples of MedicalBusiness include differents business run by health professionals.
MedicalBusiness.author: schema.org

MedicalCause.name: MedicalCause
MedicalCause.description:
Schema.org/MedicalCause
The causative agent(s) that are responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in a medical condition, symptom or sign. In this schema, unless otherwise specified this is meant to be the proximate cause of the medical condition, symptom or sign. The proximate cause is defined as the causative agent that most directly results in the medical condition, symptom or sign. For example, the HIV virus could be considered a cause of AIDS. Or in a diagnostic context, if a patient fell and sustained a hip fracture and two days later sustained a pulmonary embolism which eventuated in a cardiac arrest, the cause of the cardiac arrest (the proximate cause) would be the pulmonary embolism and not the fall. Medical causes can include cardiovascular, chemical, dermatologic, endocrine, environmental, gastroenterologic, genetic, hematologic, gynecologic, iatrogenic, infectious, musculoskeletal, neurologic, nutritional, obstetric, oncologic, otolaryngologic, pharmacologic, psychiatric, pulmonary, renal, rheumatologic, toxic, traumatic, or urologic causes; medical conditions can be causes as well.
MedicalCause.author: schema.org

MedicalClinic.name: MedicalClinic
MedicalClinic.description:
Schema.org/MedicalClinic
A facility, often associated with a hospital or medical school, that is devoted to the specific diagnosis and/or healthcare. Previously limited to outpatients but with evolution it may be open to inpatients as well.
MedicalClinic.author: schema.org

MedicalCode.name: MedicalCode
MedicalCode.description:
Schema.org/MedicalCode
A code for a medical entity.
MedicalCode.author: schema.org

MedicalCondition.name: MedicalCondition
MedicalCondition.description:
Schema.org/MedicalCondition
Any condition of the human body that affects the normal functioning of a person, whether physically or mentally. Includes diseases, injuries, disabilities, disorders, syndromes, etc.
MedicalCondition.author: schema.org

MedicalConditionStage.name: MedicalConditionStage
MedicalConditionStage.description:
Schema.org/MedicalConditionStage
A stage of a medical condition, such as 'Stage IIIa'.
MedicalConditionStage.author: schema.org

MedicalContraindication.name: MedicalContraindication
MedicalContraindication.description:
Schema.org/MedicalContraindication
A condition or factor that serves as a reason to withhold a certain medical therapy. Contraindications can be absolute (there are no reasonable circumstances for undertaking a course of action) or relative (the patient is at higher risk of complications, but that these risks may be outweighed by other considerations or mitigated by other measures).
MedicalContraindication.author: schema.org

MedicalDevice.name: MedicalDevice
MedicalDevice.description:
Schema.org/MedicalDevice
Any object used in a medical capacity, such as to diagnose or treat a patient.
MedicalDevice.author: schema.org

MedicalDevicePurpose.name: MedicalDevicePurpose
MedicalDevicePurpose.description:
Schema.org/MedicalDevicePurpose
Categories of medical devices, organized by the purpose or intended use of the device.
MedicalDevicePurpose.author: schema.org

MedicalEntity.name: MedicalEntity
MedicalEntity.description:
Schema.org/MedicalEntity
The most generic type of entity related to health and the practice of medicine.
MedicalEntity.author: schema.org

MedicalEnumeration.name: MedicalEnumeration
MedicalEnumeration.description:
Schema.org/MedicalEnumeration
Enumerations related to health and the practice of medicine: A concept that is used to attribute a quality to another concept, as a qualifier, a collection of items or a listing of all of the elements of a set in medicine practice.
MedicalEnumeration.author: schema.org

MedicalEvidenceLevel.name: MedicalEvidenceLevel
MedicalEvidenceLevel.description:
Schema.org/MedicalEvidenceLevel
Level of evidence for a medical guideline. Enumerated type.
MedicalEvidenceLevel.author: schema.org

MedicalGuideline.name: MedicalGuideline
MedicalGuideline.description:
Schema.org/MedicalGuideline
Any recommendation made by a standard society (e.g. ACC/AHA) or consensus statement that denotes how to diagnose and treat a particular condition. Note: this type should be used to tag the actual guideline recommendation; if the guideline recommendation occurs in a larger scholarly article, use MedicalScholarlyArticle to tag the overall article, not this type. Note also: the organization making the recommendation should be captured in the recognizingAuthority base property of MedicalEntity.
MedicalGuideline.author: schema.org

MedicalGuidelineContraindication.name: MedicalGuidelineContraindication
MedicalGuidelineContraindication.description:
Schema.org/MedicalGuidelineContraindication
A guideline contraindication that designates a process as harmful and where quality of the data supporting the contraindication is sound.
MedicalGuidelineContraindication.author: schema.org

MedicalGuidelineRecommendation.name: MedicalGuidelineRecommendation
MedicalGuidelineRecommendation.description:
Schema.org/MedicalGuidelineRecommendation
A guideline recommendation that is regarded as efficacious and where quality of the data supporting the recommendation is sound.
MedicalGuidelineRecommendation.author: schema.org

MedicalImagingTechnique.name: MedicalImagingTechnique
MedicalImagingTechnique.description:
Schema.org/MedicalImagingTechnique
Any medical imaging modality typically used for diagnostic purposes. Enumerated type.
MedicalImagingTechnique.author: schema.org

MedicalIndication.name: MedicalIndication
MedicalIndication.description:
Schema.org/MedicalIndication
A condition or factor that indicates use of a medical therapy, including signs, symptoms, risk factors, anatomical states, etc.
MedicalIndication.author: schema.org

MedicalIntangible.name: MedicalIntangible
MedicalIntangible.description:
Schema.org/MedicalIntangible
A utility class that serves as the umbrella for a number of 'intangible' things in the medical space.
MedicalIntangible.author: schema.org

MedicalObservationalStudy.name: MedicalObservationalStudy
MedicalObservationalStudy.description:
Schema.org/MedicalObservationalStudy
An observational study is a type of medical study that attempts to infer the possible effect of a treatment through observation of a cohort of subjects over a period of time. In an observational study, the assignment of subjects into treatment groups versus control groups is outside the control of the investigator. This is in contrast with controlled studies, such as the randomized controlled trials represented by MedicalTrial, where each subject is randomly assigned to a treatment group or a control group before the start of the treatment.
MedicalObservationalStudy.author: schema.org

MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.name: MedicalObservationalStudyDesign
MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.description:
Schema.org/MedicalObservationalStudyDesign
Design models for observational medical studies. Enumerated type.
MedicalObservationalStudyDesign.author: schema.org

MedicalOrganization.name: MedicalOrganization
MedicalOrganization.description:
Schema.org/MedicalOrganization
A medical organization (physical or not), such as hospital, institution or clinic.
MedicalOrganization.author: schema.org

MedicalProcedure.name: MedicalProcedure
MedicalProcedure.description:
Schema.org/MedicalProcedure
A process of care used in either a diagnostic, therapeutic, preventive or palliative capacity that relies on invasive (surgical), non-invasive, or other techniques.
MedicalProcedure.author: schema.org

MedicalProcedureType.name: MedicalProcedureType
MedicalProcedureType.description:
Schema.org/MedicalProcedureType
An enumeration that describes different types of medical procedures.
MedicalProcedureType.author: schema.org

MedicalRiskCalculator.name: MedicalRiskCalculator
MedicalRiskCalculator.description:
Schema.org/MedicalRiskCalculator
A complex mathematical calculation requiring an online calculator, used to assess prognosis. Note: use the url property of Thing to record any URLs for online calculators.
MedicalRiskCalculator.author: schema.org

MedicalRiskEstimator.name: MedicalRiskEstimator
MedicalRiskEstimator.description:
Schema.org/MedicalRiskEstimator
Any rule set or interactive tool for estimating the risk of developing a complication or condition.
MedicalRiskEstimator.author: schema.org

MedicalRiskFactor.name: MedicalRiskFactor
MedicalRiskFactor.description:
Schema.org/MedicalRiskFactor
A risk factor is anything that increases a person's likelihood of developing or contracting a disease, medical condition, or complication.
MedicalRiskFactor.author: schema.org

MedicalRiskScore.name: MedicalRiskScore
MedicalRiskScore.description:
Schema.org/MedicalRiskScore
A simple system that adds up the number of risk factors to yield a score that is associated with prognosis, e.g. CHAD score, TIMI risk score.
MedicalRiskScore.author: schema.org

MedicalScholarlyArticle.name: MedicalScholarlyArticle
MedicalScholarlyArticle.description:
Schema.org/MedicalScholarlyArticle
A scholarly article in the medical domain.
MedicalScholarlyArticle.author: schema.org

MedicalSign.name: MedicalSign
MedicalSign.description:
Schema.org/MedicalSign
Any physical manifestation of a person's medical condition discoverable by objective diagnostic tests or physical examination.
MedicalSign.author: schema.org

MedicalSignOrSymptom.name: MedicalSignOrSymptom
MedicalSignOrSymptom.description:
Schema.org/MedicalSignOrSymptom
Any feature associated or not with a medical condition. In medicine a symptom is generally subjective while a sign is objective.
MedicalSignOrSymptom.author: schema.org

MedicalSpecialty.name: MedicalSpecialty
MedicalSpecialty.description:
Schema.org/MedicalSpecialty
Any specific branch of medical science or practice. Medical specialities include clinical specialties that pertain to particular organ systems and their respective disease states, as well as allied health specialties. Enumerated type.
MedicalSpecialty.author: schema.org

MedicalStudy.name: MedicalStudy
MedicalStudy.description:
Schema.org/MedicalStudy
A medical study is an umbrella type covering all kinds of research studies relating to human medicine or health, including observational studies and interventional trials and registries, randomized, controlled or not. When the specific type of study is known, use one of the extensions of this type, such as MedicalTrial or MedicalObservationalStudy. Also, note that this type should be used to mark up data that describes the study itself; to tag an article that publishes the results of a study, use MedicalScholarlyArticle. Note: use the code property of MedicalEntity to store study IDs, e.g. clinicaltrials.gov ID.
MedicalStudy.author: schema.org

MedicalStudyStatus.name: MedicalStudyStatus
MedicalStudyStatus.description:
Schema.org/MedicalStudyStatus
The status of a medical study. Enumerated type.
MedicalStudyStatus.author: schema.org

MedicalSymptom.name: MedicalSymptom
MedicalSymptom.description:
Schema.org/MedicalSymptom
Any complaint sensed and expressed by the patient (therefore defined as subjective)  like stomachache, lower-back pain, or fatigue.
MedicalSymptom.author: schema.org

MedicalTest.name: MedicalTest
MedicalTest.description:
Schema.org/MedicalTest
Any medical test, typically performed for diagnostic purposes.
MedicalTest.author: schema.org

MedicalTestPanel.name: MedicalTestPanel
MedicalTestPanel.description:
Schema.org/MedicalTestPanel
Any collection of tests commonly ordered together.
MedicalTestPanel.author: schema.org

MedicalTherapy.name: MedicalTherapy
MedicalTherapy.description:
Schema.org/MedicalTherapy
Any medical intervention designed to prevent, treat, and cure human diseases and medical conditions, including both curative and palliative therapies. Medical therapies are typically processes of care relying upon pharmacotherapy, behavioral therapy, supportive therapy (with fluid or nutrition for example), or detoxification (e.g. hemodialysis) aimed at improving or preventing a health condition.
MedicalTherapy.author: schema.org

MedicalTrial.name: MedicalTrial
MedicalTrial.description:
Schema.org/MedicalTrial
A medical trial is a type of medical study that uses scientific process used to compare the safety and efficacy of medical therapies or medical procedures. In general, medical trials are controlled and subjects are allocated at random to the different treatment and/or control groups.
MedicalTrial.author: schema.org

MedicalTrialDesign.name: MedicalTrialDesign
MedicalTrialDesign.description:
Schema.org/MedicalTrialDesign
Design models for medical trials. Enumerated type.
MedicalTrialDesign.author: schema.org

MedicalWebPage.name: MedicalWebPage
MedicalWebPage.description:
Schema.org/MedicalWebPage
A web page that provides medical information.
MedicalWebPage.author: schema.org

MeetingRoom.name: MeetingRoom
MeetingRoom.description:
Schema.org/MeetingRoom A meeting room, conference room, or conference hall is a room provided for singular events such as business conferences and meetings (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conference_hall).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
MeetingRoom.author: schema.org

Menu.name: Menu
Menu.description:
Schema.org/Menu
A structured representation of food or drink items available from a FoodEstablishment.
Menu.author: schema.org

MenuItem.name: MenuItem
MenuItem.description:
Schema.org/MenuItem
A food or drink item listed in a menu or menu section.
MenuItem.author: schema.org

MenuSection.name: MenuSection
MenuSection.description:
Schema.org/MenuSection
A sub-grouping of food or drink items in a menu. E.g. courses (such as 'Dinner', 'Breakfast', etc.), specific type of dishes (such as 'Meat', 'Vegan', 'Drinks', etc.), or some other classification made by the menu provider.
MenuSection.author: schema.org

MerchantReturnEnumeration.name: MerchantReturnEnumeration
MerchantReturnEnumeration.description:
Schema.org/MerchantReturnEnumeration
MerchantReturnEnumeration enumerates several kinds of product return policy. Note that this structure may not capture all aspects of the policy.
MerchantReturnEnumeration.author: schema.org

MerchantReturnPolicy.name: MerchantReturnPolicy
MerchantReturnPolicy.description:
Schema.org/MerchantReturnPolicy
A MerchantReturnPolicy provides information about product return policies associated with an [[Organization]] or [[Product]].
MerchantReturnPolicy.author: schema.org

Message.name: Message
Message.description:
Schema.org/Message
A single message from a sender to one or more organizations or people.
Message.author: schema.org

MiddleSchool.name: MiddleSchool
MiddleSchool.description:
Schema.org/MiddleSchool
A middle school (typically for children aged around 11-14, although this varies somewhat).
MiddleSchool.author: schema.org

MobileApplication.name: MobileApplication
MobileApplication.description:
Schema.org/MobileApplication
A software application designed specifically to work well on a mobile device such as a telephone.
MobileApplication.author: schema.org

MobilePhoneStore.name: MobilePhoneStore
MobilePhoneStore.description:
Schema.org/MobilePhoneStore
A store that sells mobile phones and related accessories.
MobilePhoneStore.author: schema.org

MonetaryAmount.name: MonetaryAmount
MonetaryAmount.description:
Schema.org/MonetaryAmount
A monetary value or range. This type can be used to describe an amount of money such as $50 USD, or a range as in describing a bank account being suitable for a balance between £1,000 and £1,000,000 GBP, or the value of a salary, etc. It is recommended to use [[PriceSpecification]] Types to describe the price of an Offer, Invoice, etc.
MonetaryAmount.author: schema.org

MonetaryAmountDistribution.name: MonetaryAmountDistribution
MonetaryAmountDistribution.description:
Schema.org/MonetaryAmountDistribution
A statistical distribution of monetary amounts.
MonetaryAmountDistribution.author: schema.org

MoneyTransfer.name: MoneyTransfer
MoneyTransfer.description:
Schema.org/MoneyTransfer
The act of transferring money from one place to another place. This may occur electronically or physically.
MoneyTransfer.author: schema.org

MortgageLoan.name: MortgageLoan
MortgageLoan.description:
Schema.org/MortgageLoan
A loan in which property or real estate is used as collateral. (A loan securitized against some real estate).
MortgageLoan.author: schema.org

Motel.name: Motel
Motel.description:
Schema.org/Motel A motel.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.
Motel.author: schema.org

Motorcycle.name: Motorcycle
Motorcycle.description:
Schema.org/Motorcycle
A motorcycle or motorbike is a single-track, two-wheeled motor vehicle.
Motorcycle.author: schema.org

MotorizedBicycle.name: MotorizedBicycle
MotorizedBicycle.description:
Schema.org/MotorizedBicycle
A motorized bicycle is a bicycle with an attached motor used to power the vehicle, or to assist with pedaling.
MotorizedBicycle.author: schema.org

Mountain.name: Mountain
Mountain.description:
Schema.org/Mountain
A mountain, like Mount Whitney or Mount Everest.
Mountain.author: schema.org

MoveAction.name: MoveAction
MoveAction.description:
Schema.org/MoveAction
The act of an agent relocating to a place.

Related actions:

* [[TransferAction]]: Unlike TransferAction, the subject of the move is a living Person or Organization rather than an inanimate object.
MoveAction.author: schema.org

MovieClip.name: MovieClip
MovieClip.description:
Schema.org/MovieClip
A short segment/part of a movie.
MovieClip.author: schema.org

MovieSeries.name: MovieSeries
MovieSeries.description:
Schema.org/MovieSeries
A series of movies. Included movies can be indicated with the hasPart property.
MovieSeries.author: schema.org

Muscle.name: Muscle
Muscle.description:
Schema.org/Muscle
A muscle is an anatomical structure consisting of a contractile form of tissue that animals use to effect movement.
Muscle.author: schema.org

MusicAlbum.name: MusicAlbum
MusicAlbum.description:
Schema.org/MusicAlbum
A collection of music tracks.
MusicAlbum.author: schema.org

MusicAlbumProductionType.name: MusicAlbumProductionType
MusicAlbumProductionType.description:
Schema.org/MusicAlbumProductionType
Classification of the album by it's type of content: soundtrack, live album, studio album, etc.
MusicAlbumProductionType.author: schema.org

MusicAlbumReleaseType.name: MusicAlbumReleaseType
MusicAlbumReleaseType.description:
Schema.org/MusicAlbumReleaseType
The kind of release which this album is: single, EP or album.
MusicAlbumReleaseType.author: schema.org

MusicGroup.name: MusicGroup
MusicGroup.description:
Schema.org/MusicGroup
A musical group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a choir. Can also be a solo musician.
MusicGroup.author: schema.org

MusicPlaylist.name: MusicPlaylist
MusicPlaylist.description:
Schema.org/MusicPlaylist
A collection of music tracks in playlist form.
MusicPlaylist.author: schema.org

MusicRecording.name: MusicRecording
MusicRecording.description:
Schema.org/MusicRecording
A music recording (track), usually a single song.
MusicRecording.author: schema.org

MusicRelease.name: MusicRelease
MusicRelease.description:
Schema.org/MusicRelease
A MusicRelease is a specific release of a music album.
MusicRelease.author: schema.org

MusicReleaseFormatType.name: MusicReleaseFormatType
MusicReleaseFormatType.description:
Schema.org/MusicReleaseFormatType
Format of this release (the type of recording media used, ie. compact disc, digital media, LP, etc.).
MusicReleaseFormatType.author: schema.org

NLNonprofitType.name: NLNonprofitType
NLNonprofitType.description:
Schema.org/NLNonprofitType
NLNonprofitType: Non-profit organization type originating from the Netherlands.
NLNonprofitType.author: schema.org

Nerve.name: Nerve
Nerve.description:
Schema.org/Nerve
A common pathway for the electrochemical nerve impulses that are transmitted along each of the axons.
Nerve.author: schema.org

NewsArticle.name: NewsArticle
NewsArticle.description:
Schema.org/NewsArticle
A NewsArticle is an article whose content reports news, or provides background context and supporting materials for understanding the news.

A more detailed overview of [schema.org News markup](/docs/news.html) is also available.
NewsArticle.author: schema.org

NewsMediaOrganization.name: NewsMediaOrganization
NewsMediaOrganization.description:
Schema.org/NewsMediaOrganization
A News/Media organization such as a newspaper or TV station.
NewsMediaOrganization.author: schema.org

Newspaper.name: Newspaper
Newspaper.description:
Schema.org/Newspaper
A publication containing information about varied topics that are pertinent to general information, a geographic area, or a specific subject matter (i.e. business, culture, education). Often published daily.
Newspaper.author: schema.org

NonprofitType.name: NonprofitType
NonprofitType.description:
Schema.org/NonprofitType
NonprofitType enumerates several kinds of official non-profit types of which a non-profit organization can be.
NonprofitType.author: schema.org

NoteDigitalDocument.name: NoteDigitalDocument
NoteDigitalDocument.description:
Schema.org/NoteDigitalDocument
A file containing a note, primarily for the author.
NoteDigitalDocument.author: schema.org

NutritionInformation.name: NutritionInformation
NutritionInformation.description:
Schema.org/NutritionInformation
Nutritional information about the recipe.
NutritionInformation.author: schema.org

Observation.name: Observation
Observation.description:
Schema.org/Observation
Instances of the class [[Observation]] are used to specify observations about an entity (which may or may not be an instance of a [[StatisticalPopulation]]), at a particular time. The principal properties of an [[Observation]] are [[observedNode]], [[measuredProperty]], [[measuredValue]] (or [[median]], etc.) and [[observationDate]] ([[measuredProperty]] properties can, but need not always, be W3C RDF Data Cube "measure properties", as in the [lifeExpectancy example](https://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-data-cube/#dsd-example)).
See also [[StatisticalPopulation]], and the [data and datasets](/docs/data-and-datasets.html) overview for more details.
Observation.author: schema.org

OccupationalTherapy.name: OccupationalTherapy
OccupationalTherapy.description:
Schema.org/OccupationalTherapy
A treatment of people with physical, emotional, or social problems, using purposeful activity to help them overcome or learn to deal with their problems.
OccupationalTherapy.author: schema.org

OceanBodyOfWater.name: OceanBodyOfWater
OceanBodyOfWater.description:
Schema.org/OceanBodyOfWater
An ocean (for example, the Pacific).
OceanBodyOfWater.author: schema.org

Offer.name: Offer
Offer.description:
Schema.org/Offer
An offer to transfer some rights to an item or to provide a service — for example, an offer to sell tickets to an event, to rent the DVD of a movie, to stream a TV show over the internet, to repair a motorcycle, or to loan a book.

Note: As the [[businessFunction]] property, which identifies the form of offer (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose), defaults to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell; an Offer without a defined businessFunction value can be assumed to be an offer to sell.

For [GTIN](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin)-related fields, see [Check Digit calculator](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/support/check_digit_calculator) and [validation guide](http://www.gs1us.org/resources/standards/gtin-validation-guide) from [GS1](http://www.gs1.org/).
Offer.author: schema.org

OfferCatalog.name: OfferCatalog
OfferCatalog.description:
Schema.org/OfferCatalog
An OfferCatalog is an ItemList that contains related Offers and/or further OfferCatalogs that are offeredBy the same provider.
OfferCatalog.author: schema.org

OfferForLease.name: OfferForLease
OfferForLease.description:
Schema.org/OfferForLease
An [[OfferForLease]] in Schema.org represents an [[Offer]] to lease out something, i.e. an [[Offer]] whose
 [[businessFunction]] is [lease out](http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut.). See [Good Relations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GoodRelations) for
 background on the underlying concepts.
OfferForLease.author: schema.org

OfferForPurchase.name: OfferForPurchase
OfferForPurchase.description:
Schema.org/OfferForPurchase
An [[OfferForPurchase]] in Schema.org represents an [[Offer]] to sell something, i.e. an [[Offer]] whose
 [[businessFunction]] is [sell](http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.). See [Good Relations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GoodRelations) for
 background on the underlying concepts.
OfferForPurchase.author: schema.org

OfferItemCondition.name: OfferItemCondition
OfferItemCondition.description:
Schema.org/OfferItemCondition
A list of possible conditions for the item.
OfferItemCondition.author: schema.org

OfferShippingDetails.name: OfferShippingDetails
OfferShippingDetails.description:
Schema.org/OfferShippingDetails
OfferShippingDetails represents information about shipping destinations.

Multiple of these entities can be used to represent different shipping rates for different destinations:

One entity for Alaska/Hawaii. A different one for continental US.A different one for all France.

Multiple of these entities can be used to represent different shipping costs and delivery times.

Two entities that are identical but differ in rate and time:

e.g. Cheaper and slower: $5 in 5-7days
or Fast and expensive: $15 in 1-2 days.
OfferShippingDetails.author: schema.org

OnDemandEvent.name: OnDemandEvent
OnDemandEvent.description:
Schema.org/OnDemandEvent
A publication event e.g. catch-up TV or radio podcast, during which a program is available on-demand.
OnDemandEvent.author: schema.org

OpeningHoursSpecification.name: OpeningHoursSpecification
OpeningHoursSpecification.description:
Schema.org/OpeningHoursSpecification
A structured value providing information about the opening hours of a place or a certain service inside a place.


The place is __open__ if the [[opens]] property is specified, and __closed__ otherwise.

If the value for the [[closes]] property is less than the value for the [[opens]] property then the hour range is assumed to span over the next day.
OpeningHoursSpecification.author: schema.org

OpinionNewsArticle.name: OpinionNewsArticle
OpinionNewsArticle.description:
Schema.org/OpinionNewsArticle
An [[OpinionNewsArticle]] is a [[NewsArticle]] that primarily expresses opinions rather than journalistic reporting of news and events. For example, a [[NewsArticle]] consisting of a column or [[Blog]]/[[BlogPosting]] entry in the Opinions section of a news publication.
OpinionNewsArticle.author: schema.org

Optician.name: Optician
Optician.description:
Schema.org/Optician
A store that sells reading glasses and similar devices for improving vision.
Optician.author: schema.org

Order.name: Order
Order.description:
Schema.org/Order
An order is a confirmation of a transaction (a receipt), which can contain multiple line items, each represented by an Offer that has been accepted by the customer.
Order.author: schema.org

OrderAction.name: OrderAction
OrderAction.description:
Schema.org/OrderAction
An agent orders an object/product/service to be delivered/sent.
OrderAction.author: schema.org

OrderItem.name: OrderItem
OrderItem.description:
Schema.org/OrderItem
An order item is a line of an order. It includes the quantity and shipping details of a bought offer.
OrderItem.author: schema.org

OrderStatus.name: OrderStatus
OrderStatus.description:
Schema.org/OrderStatus
Enumerated status values for Order.
OrderStatus.author: schema.org

Organization.name: Organization
Organization.description:
Schema.org/Organization
An organization such as a school, NGO, corporation, club, etc.
Organization.author: schema.org

OrganizationRole.name: OrganizationRole
OrganizationRole.description:
Schema.org/OrganizationRole
A subclass of Role used to describe roles within organizations.
OrganizationRole.author: schema.org

OrganizeAction.name: OrganizeAction
OrganizeAction.description:
Schema.org/OrganizeAction
The act of manipulating/administering/supervising/controlling one or more objects.
OrganizeAction.author: schema.org

OwnershipInfo.name: OwnershipInfo
OwnershipInfo.description:
Schema.org/OwnershipInfo
A structured value providing information about when a certain organization or person owned a certain product.
OwnershipInfo.author: schema.org

PaintAction.name: PaintAction
PaintAction.description:
Schema.org/PaintAction
The act of producing a painting, typically with paint and canvas as instruments.
PaintAction.author: schema.org

PalliativeProcedure.name: PalliativeProcedure
PalliativeProcedure.description:
Schema.org/PalliativeProcedure
A medical procedure intended primarily for palliative purposes, aimed at relieving the symptoms of an underlying health condition.
PalliativeProcedure.author: schema.org

ParcelDelivery.name: ParcelDelivery
ParcelDelivery.description:
Schema.org/ParcelDelivery
The delivery of a parcel either via the postal service or a commercial service.
ParcelDelivery.author: schema.org

ParentAudience.name: ParentAudience
ParentAudience.description:
Schema.org/ParentAudience
A set of characteristics describing parents, who can be interested in viewing some content.
ParentAudience.author: schema.org

ParkingFacility.name: ParkingFacility
ParkingFacility.description:
Schema.org/ParkingFacility
A parking lot or other parking facility.
ParkingFacility.author: schema.org

PathologyTest.name: PathologyTest
PathologyTest.description:
Schema.org/PathologyTest
A medical test performed by a laboratory that typically involves examination of a tissue sample by a pathologist.
PathologyTest.author: schema.org

Patient.name: Patient
Patient.description:
Schema.org/Patient
A patient is any person recipient of health care services.
Patient.author: schema.org

PawnShop.name: PawnShop
PawnShop.description:
Schema.org/PawnShop
A shop that will buy, or lend money against the security of, personal possessions.
PawnShop.author: schema.org

PayAction.name: PayAction
PayAction.description:
Schema.org/PayAction
An agent pays a price to a participant.
PayAction.author: schema.org

PaymentCard.name: PaymentCard
PaymentCard.description:
Schema.org/PaymentCard
A payment method using a credit, debit, store or other card to associate the payment with an account.
PaymentCard.author: schema.org

PaymentChargeSpecification.name: PaymentChargeSpecification
PaymentChargeSpecification.description:
Schema.org/PaymentChargeSpecification
The costs of settling the payment using a particular payment method.
PaymentChargeSpecification.author: schema.org

PaymentMethod.name: PaymentMethod
PaymentMethod.description:
Schema.org/PaymentMethod
A payment method is a standardized procedure for transferring the monetary amount for a purchase. Payment methods are characterized by the legal and technical structures used, and by the organization or group carrying out the transaction.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByBankTransferInAdvance
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByInvoice
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Cash
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#CheckInAdvance
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#COD
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DirectDebit
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#GoogleCheckout
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PayPal
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PaySwarm
PaymentMethod.author: schema.org

PaymentService.name: PaymentService
PaymentService.description:
Schema.org/PaymentService
A Service to transfer funds from a person or organization to a beneficiary person or organization.
PaymentService.author: schema.org

PaymentStatusType.name: PaymentStatusType
PaymentStatusType.description:
Schema.org/PaymentStatusType
A specific payment status. For example, PaymentDue, PaymentComplete, etc.
PaymentStatusType.author: schema.org

PeopleAudience.name: PeopleAudience
PeopleAudience.description:
Schema.org/PeopleAudience
A set of characteristics belonging to people, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.
PeopleAudience.author: schema.org

PerformAction.name: PerformAction
PerformAction.description:
Schema.org/PerformAction
The act of participating in performance arts.
PerformAction.author: schema.org

PerformanceRole.name: PerformanceRole
PerformanceRole.description:
Schema.org/PerformanceRole
A PerformanceRole is a Role that some entity places with regard to a theatrical performance, e.g. in a Movie, TVSeries etc.
PerformanceRole.author: schema.org

PerformingArtsTheater.name: PerformingArtsTheater
PerformingArtsTheater.description:
Schema.org/PerformingArtsTheater
A theater or other performing art center.
PerformingArtsTheater.author: schema.org

PerformingGroup.name: PerformingGroup
PerformingGroup.description:
Schema.org/PerformingGroup
A performance group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a circus.
PerformingGroup.author: schema.org

Periodical.name: Periodical
Periodical.description:
Schema.org/Periodical
A publication in any medium issued in successive parts bearing numerical or chronological designations and intended, such as a magazine, scholarly journal, or newspaper to continue indefinitely.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).
Periodical.author: schema.org

Permit.name: Permit
Permit.description:
Schema.org/Permit
A permit issued by an organization, e.g. a parking pass.
Permit.author: schema.org

Person.name: Person
Person.description:
Schema.org/Person
A person (alive, dead, undead, or fictional).
Person.author: schema.org

PhotographAction.name: PhotographAction
PhotographAction.description:
Schema.org/PhotographAction
The act of capturing still images of objects using a camera.
PhotographAction.author: schema.org

PhysicalActivity.name: PhysicalActivity
PhysicalActivity.description:
Schema.org/PhysicalActivity
Any bodily activity that enhances or maintains physical fitness and overall health and wellness. Includes activity that is part of daily living and routine, structured exercise, and exercise prescribed as part of a medical treatment or recovery plan.
PhysicalActivity.author: schema.org

PhysicalActivityCategory.name: PhysicalActivityCategory
PhysicalActivityCategory.description:
Schema.org/PhysicalActivityCategory
Categories of physical activity, organized by physiologic classification.
PhysicalActivityCategory.author: schema.org

PhysicalExam.name: PhysicalExam
PhysicalExam.description:
Schema.org/PhysicalExam
A type of physical examination of a patient performed by a physician.
PhysicalExam.author: schema.org

PhysicalTherapy.name: PhysicalTherapy
PhysicalTherapy.description:
Schema.org/PhysicalTherapy
A process of progressive physical care and rehabilitation aimed at improving a health condition.
PhysicalTherapy.author: schema.org

PlaceOfWorship.name: PlaceOfWorship
PlaceOfWorship.description:
Schema.org/PlaceOfWorship
Place of worship, such as a church, synagogue, or mosque.
PlaceOfWorship.author: schema.org

PlanAction.name: PlanAction
PlanAction.description:
Schema.org/PlanAction
The act of planning the execution of an event/task/action/reservation/plan to a future date.
PlanAction.author: schema.org

Play.name: Play
Play.description:
Schema.org/Play
A play is a form of literature, usually consisting of dialogue between characters, intended for theatrical performance rather than just reading. Note the peformance of a Play would be a [[TheaterEvent]] - the *Play* being the [[workPerformed]].
Play.author: schema.org

PlayAction.name: PlayAction
PlayAction.description:
Schema.org/PlayAction
The act of playing/exercising/training/performing for enjoyment, leisure, recreation, Competition or exercise.

Related actions:

* [[ListenAction]]: Unlike ListenAction (which is under ConsumeAction), PlayAction refers to performing for an audience or at an event, rather than consuming music.
* [[WatchAction]]: Unlike WatchAction (which is under ConsumeAction), PlayAction refers to showing/displaying for an audience or at an event, rather than consuming visual content.
PlayAction.author: schema.org

PodcastEpisode.name: PodcastEpisode
PodcastEpisode.description:
Schema.org/PodcastEpisode
A single episode of a podcast series.
PodcastEpisode.author: schema.org

PodcastSeason.name: PodcastSeason
PodcastSeason.description:
Schema.org/PodcastSeason
A single season of a podcast. Many podcasts do not break down into separate seasons. In that case, PodcastSeries should be used.
PodcastSeason.author: schema.org

PodcastSeries.name: PodcastSeries
PodcastSeries.description:
Schema.org/PodcastSeries
A podcast is an episodic series of digital audio or video files which a user can download and listen to.
PodcastSeries.author: schema.org

PostalCodeRangeSpecification.name: PostalCodeRangeSpecification
PostalCodeRangeSpecification.description:
Schema.org/PostalCodeRangeSpecification
